INSERT INTO `flashcards_flashcard` VALUES (1,'What is the equation of a circle with center at the origin $(0, 0)$ and radius $r = 5$?','flashcards/front/front_1.png','$x^2 + y^2 = 25$','flashcards/back/back_1.png','$x^2 + y^2 = 5$','$(x - 0)^2 + (y - 0)^2 = 5$','$x + y = 25$','For a circle centered at the origin with radius $r$, the equation is $x^2 + y^2 = r^2$. Since $r = 5$, we have $x^2 + y^2 = 5^2 = 25$.',1,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.681156','2025-12-29 11:01:00.681184',1),(2,'What is the probability of an **impossible** event?','','0 (zero)','','1','0.5','Cannot be determined','An impossible event has a probability of 0 because it cannot occur. For example, the probability of rolling a 7 on a standard six-sided die is 0.',1,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.685202','2025-12-29 11:01:00.685226',2),(3,'What is the probability of a **certain** event?','','1','','0','100','Infinity','A certain event has a probability of 1 because it will definitely occur. For example, the probability of rolling a number between 1 and 6 on a standard die is 1.',2,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.685963','2025-12-29 11:01:00.685985',2),(4,'What is the formula for calculating the probability of event A?','','$P(A) = \\frac{\\text{Number of favorable outcomes}}{\\text{Total number of possible outcomes}}$','','$P(A) = \\text{favorable} \\times \\text{total}$','$P(A) = \\text{total} - \\text{favorable}$','$P(A) = \\frac{\\text{Total}}{\\text{Favorable}}$','This is the fundamental probability formula. For example, the probability of rolling a 3 on a die is $\\frac{1}{6}$ (1 favorable outcome out of 6 possible outcomes).',3,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.686668','2025-12-29 11:01:00.686690',2),(5,'What does $P(A\')$ or $P(\\overline{A})$ represent?','','The probability of event A NOT occurring (complement of A)','','The probability of event A occurring twice','The probability of event A divided by 2','The inverse of the probability of A','$P(A\') = 1 - P(A)$. This is called the complement rule. If the probability of rain is 0.3, then the probability of no rain is $1 - 0.3 = 0.7$.',4,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.687363','2025-12-29 11:01:00.687383',2),(6,'What is the range of all probability values?','','$0 \\leq P(A) \\leq 1$','','$-1 \\leq P(A) \\leq 1$','$0 \\leq P(A) \\leq 100$','$P(A) > 0$','All probabilities must be between 0 and 1 inclusive. 0 represents impossibility, 1 represents certainty, and values in between represent varying degrees of likelihood.',5,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.688157','2025-12-29 11:01:00.688179',2),(7,'Two events are **mutually exclusive** if:','','They cannot both occur at the same time','','They always occur together','One event affects the probability of the other','They have equal probabilities','Mutually exclusive events have no overlap. For example, rolling a 2 and rolling a 5 on a single die roll are mutually exclusive events - you cannot roll both at the same time.',6,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.688865','2025-12-29 11:01:00.688886',2),(8,'What is the Addition Rule for mutually exclusive events A and B?','','$P(A \\text{ or } B) = P(A) + P(B)$','','$P(A \\text{ or } B) = P(A) \\times P(B)$','$P(A \\text{ or } B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \\cap B)$','$P(A \\text{ or } B) = \\frac{P(A)}{P(B)}$','For mutually exclusive events, we simply add the probabilities. Example: The probability of rolling a 2 OR a 5 is $\\frac{1}{6} + \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{2}{6} = \\frac{1}{3}$.',7,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.689594','2025-12-29 11:01:00.689616',2),(9,'What is the Multiplication Rule for **independent** events A and B?','','$P(A \\text{ and } B) = P(A) \\times P(B)$','','$P(A \\text{ and } B) = P(A) + P(B)$','$P(A \\text{ and } B) = P(A) - P(B)$','$P(A \\text{ and } B) = \\frac{P(A)}{P(B)}$','For independent events, we multiply the probabilities. Example: The probability of flipping heads AND rolling a 6 is $\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{1}{6} = \\frac{1}{12}$.',8,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.690657','2025-12-29 11:01:00.690686',2),(10,'Two events A and B are **independent** if:','','The occurrence of one does not affect the probability of the other','','They cannot occur at the same time','They always occur together','$P(A) = P(B)$','Independent events do not influence each other. Example: Flipping a coin and rolling a die are independent - the coin result does not change the die probabilities.',9,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.691740','2025-12-29 11:01:00.691776',2),(11,'What does $P(A|B)$ represent?','','The conditional probability of A given that B has occurred','','The probability of A or B','The probability of A and B','The probability of A divided by the probability of B','This is read as \"probability of A given B\". It represents the probability of A occurring when we know B has already occurred. Formula: $P(A|B) = \\frac{P(A \\cap B)}{P(B)}$',10,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.692882','2025-12-29 11:01:00.692916',2),(12,'What is the derivative of a **constant** $c$?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(c) = 0$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(c) = 1$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(c) = c$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(c) = x$','The derivative of any constant is always 0 because constants do not change. For example, $\\frac{d}{dx}(5) = 0$ and $\\frac{d}{dx}(\\pi) = 0$.',1,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.698861','2025-12-29 11:01:00.698904',3),(13,'What is the **Power Rule** for differentiation?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(x^n) = nx^{n-1}$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(x^n) = x^{n+1}$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(x^n) = nx^{n}$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(x^n) = (n-1)x^{n-1}$','The power rule states: bring down the exponent as a coefficient and reduce the exponent by 1. Example: $\\frac{d}{dx}(x^3) = 3x^{2}$',2,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.699942','2025-12-29 11:01:00.699985',3),(14,'What is the derivative of $\\sin(x)$?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\sin x) = \\cos x$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\sin x) = -\\cos x$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\sin x) = \\sin x$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\sin x) = -\\sin x$','The derivative of sine is cosine. This is one of the fundamental trigonometric derivatives you need to memorize.',3,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.701258','2025-12-29 11:01:00.701288',3),(15,'What is the derivative of $\\cos(x)$?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\cos x) = -\\sin x$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\cos x) = \\sin x$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\cos x) = \\cos x$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\cos x) = -\\cos x$','The derivative of cosine is negative sine. Note the negative sign! This is important to remember.',4,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.702152','2025-12-29 11:01:00.702178',3),(16,'What is the derivative of $e^x$?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(e^x) = e^x$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(e^x) = xe^{x-1}$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(e^x) = 0$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(e^x) = e$','The exponential function $e^x$ is special - it is its own derivative! This makes it very useful in calculus.',5,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.702935','2025-12-29 11:01:00.702960',3),(17,'What is the derivative of $\\ln(x)$?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\ln x) = \\frac{1}{x}$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\ln x) = x$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\ln x) = \\frac{1}{x^2}$','$\\frac{d}{dx}(\\ln x) = e^x$','The derivative of the natural logarithm is $\\frac{1}{x}$. This is valid for $x > 0$.',6,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.703648','2025-12-29 11:01:00.703671',3),(18,'What is the **Chain Rule**?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(g(x))] = f\'(g(x)) \\cdot g\'(x)$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(g(x))] = f\'(x) \\cdot g\'(x)$','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(g(x))] = f(x) \\cdot g(x)$','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(g(x))] = f\'(x) + g\'(x)$','The chain rule is used for composite functions. Differentiate the outer function, multiply by the derivative of the inner function. Example: $\\frac{d}{dx}(\\sin(x^2)) = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot 2x$',7,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.704610','2025-12-29 11:01:00.704644',3),(19,'What is the **Product Rule**?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(x)g(x)] = f\'(x)g(x) + f(x)g\'(x)$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(x)g(x)] = f\'(x) \\cdot g\'(x)$','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(x)g(x)] = f\'(x)g(x)$','$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(x)g(x)] = f(x) + g(x)$','When differentiating a product, use: (derivative of first  second) + (first  derivative of second). Example: $\\frac{d}{dx}(x \\sin x) = \\sin x + x \\cos x$',8,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.705672','2025-12-29 11:01:00.705709',3),(20,'What is the **Quotient Rule**?','','$\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[\\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\\right] = \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) - f(x)g\'(x)}{[g(x)]^2}$','','$\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[\\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\\right] = \\frac{f\'(x)}{g\'(x)}$','$\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[\\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\\right] = \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) + f(x)g\'(x)}{[g(x)]^2}$','$\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[\\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\\right] = \\frac{f(x) - g(x)}{g(x)}$','The quotient rule: (bottom  derivative of top - top  derivative of bottom) all over (bottom squared). Remember: \"lo d-hi minus hi d-lo over lo-lo\"',9,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.706569','2025-12-29 11:01:00.706592',3),(21,'If $y = x^3 + 2x$, what is $\\frac{dy}{dx}$?','','$\\frac{dy}{dx} = 3x^2 + 2$','','$\\frac{dy}{dx} = 3x^2 + 2x$','$\\frac{dy}{dx} = x^2 + 2$','$\\frac{dy}{dx} = 3x^3 + 2x$','Apply the power rule to each term: $\\frac{d}{dx}(x^3) = 3x^2$ and $\\frac{d}{dx}(2x) = 2$. Add them together to get $3x^2 + 2$.',10,'2025-12-29 11:01:00.707334','2025-12-29 11:01:00.707363',3),(22,'What is the quadratic formula for solving $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$?','','$x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$','','$x = \\frac{b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$','$x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 + 4ac}}{2a}$','$x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{4ac - b^2}}{2a}$','',1,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.266968','2026-01-05 16:56:59.267025',5),(23,'What does the discriminant $\\Delta = b^2 - 4ac$ tell us about a quadratic equation?','','If $\\Delta > 0$: two real roots; $\\Delta = 0$: one repeated root; $\\Delta < 0$: no real roots','','If $\\Delta > 0$: one root; $\\Delta = 0$: no roots; $\\Delta < 0$: two roots','If $\\Delta > 0$: no roots; $\\Delta = 0$: one root; $\\Delta < 0$: two roots','The discriminant only tells us the coefficient values','',2,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.272404','2026-01-05 16:56:59.272443',5),(24,'What is the difference of two squares factorization?','','$a^2 - b^2 = (a + b)(a - b)$','','$a^2 - b^2 = (a - b)^2$','$a^2 - b^2 = (a + b)^2$','$a^2 - b^2 = a(a - b)$','',3,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.273703','2026-01-05 16:56:59.273738',5),(25,'What are the laws of indices for multi