41,'What is the **perpendicular bisector** property for points on a circle?','','The **perpendicular bisector** of any chord passes through the **centre** of the circle','','The perpendicular bisector of any chord is parallel to the diameter','The perpendicular bisector of any chord passes through the midpoint of the arc','The perpendicular bisector of any chord is tangent to the circle','This is useful for finding the centre of a circle: draw two chords, construct their perpendicular bisectors, and they intersect at the centre.',10,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.724546','2026-01-05 16:56:59.724595',16),(142,'What is the relationship between **equal chords** and their distance from the centre?','','Equal chords are **equidistant** from the centre of the circle','','Equal chords are always parallel to each other','Equal chords must be perpendicular to each other','Equal chords always intersect at the centre','Conversely, chords that are equidistant from the centre are equal in length. The perpendicular distance from centre to chord determines chord length.',11,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.726266','2026-01-05 16:56:59.726310',16),(143,'What is the equation of a circle with center at the origin $(0, 0)$ and radius $r = 5$?','','$x^2 + y^2 = 25$','','$x^2 + y^2 = 5$','$(x - 0)^2 + (y - 0)^2 = 5$','$x + y = 25$','For a circle centered at the origin with radius $r$, the equation is $x^2 + y^2 = r^2$. Since $r = 5$, we have $x^2 + y^2 = 5^2 = 25$.',1,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.760210','2026-01-05 16:56:59.760268',17),(144,'What is the formula for the **slope (gradient)** of a line through points $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$?','','$m = \\frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$ or $m = \\frac{\\text{rise}}{\\text{run}}$','','$m = \\frac{x_2 - x_1}{y_2 - y_1}$','$m = \\frac{y_2 + y_1}{x_2 + x_1}$','$m = y_2 - y_1 - x_2 + x_1$','The slope measures the steepness of the line: change in y divided by change in x. Also written as y/x.',1,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.765686','2026-01-05 16:56:59.765756',18),(145,'What is the **slope-intercept form** (y = mx + c form) of a line equation?','','$y = mx + c$ where $m$ is the slope and $c$ is the y-intercept','','$x = my + c$ where $m$ is the slope and $c$ is the x-intercept','$y = cx + m$ where $c$ is the slope and $m$ is the y-intercept','$y = m(x + c)$ where $m$ is the slope and $c$ is the y-intercept','This is the most common form. The y-intercept c is where the line crosses the y-axis (when x = 0).',2,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.767719','2026-01-05 16:56:59.767786',18),(146,'What is the **point-slope form** of a line with slope $m$ passing through point $(x_1, y_1)$?','','$y - y_1 = m(x - x_1)$','','$y + y_1 = m(x + x_1)$','$y = m(x - x_1) + y_1$','$x - x_1 = m(y - y_1)$','This form is useful when you know a point on the line and the slope. It can be rearranged to y = mx + c form.',3,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.769980','2026-01-05 16:56:59.770037',18),(147,'What is the relationship between the slopes of **parallel lines**?','','Parallel lines have **equal slopes**: if lines are parallel, then $m_1 = m_2$','','Parallel lines have slopes that multiply to -1','Parallel lines have reciprocal slopes','Parallel lines have slopes that sum to 0','Lines with the same slope never intersect (they are parallel), unless they are the same line.',4,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.771492','2026-01-05 16:56:59.771532',18),(148,'What is the relationship between the slopes of **perpendicular lines**?','','Perpendicular lines have slopes whose **product is -1**: $m_1 \\times m_2 = -1$ or $m_2 = -\\frac{1}{m_1}$','','Perpendicular lines have equal slopes','Perpendicular lines have slopes that sum to -1','Perpendicular lines have slopes with a ratio of 2:1','The slopes are negative reciprocals of each other. If one line has slope 2, a perpendicular line has slope -1/2.',5,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.772794','2026-01-05 16:56:59.772833',18),(149,'What is the formula for the **distance** between two points $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$?','','$d = \\sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}$','','$d = (x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2$','$d = \\sqrt{(x_2 + x_1)^2 + (y_2 + y_1)^2}$','$d = |x_2 - x_1| + |y_2 - y_1|$','This is derived from Pythagoras\' theorem. It calculates the straight-line distance between two points.',6,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.774570','2026-01-05 16:56:59.774612',18),(150,'What is the formula for the **midpoint** of the line segment joining $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$?','','$M = \\left(\\frac{x_1 + x_2}{2}, \\frac{y_1 + y_2}{2}\\right)$','','$M = \\left(\\frac{x_2 - x_1}{2}, \\frac{y_2 - y_1}{2}\\right)$','$M = (x_1 + x_2, y_1 + y_2)$','$M = \\left(\\sqrt{x_1x_2}, \\sqrt{y_1y_2}\\right)$','The midpoint is found by averaging the x-coordinates and averaging the y-coordinates.',7,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.775902','2026-01-05 16:56:59.775941',18),(151,'What is the **general form** (ax + by + c = 0 form) of a line equation?','','$ax + by + c = 0$ where $a$, $b$, $c$ are constants and $a$, $b$ are not both zero','','$ax + by = c$ where $c$ must equal zero','$ax^2 + by^2 + c = 0$','$y = ax + b + c$','Any linear equation can be written in this form. From this, you can find the slope as m = -a/b (if b  0).',8,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.777202','2026-01-05 16:56:59.777241',18),(152,'What is the slope of a **horizontal line**?','','The slope is **0** (equation form: $y = c$ where $c$ is constant)','','The slope is undefined','The slope is 1','The slope is infinite','A horizontal line has no rise (y = 0), so m = 0/x = 0. All points have the same y-coordinate.',9,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.804296','2026-01-05 16:56:59.804371',18),(153,'What is the slope of a **vertical line**?','','The slope is **undefined** (equation form: $x = c$ where $c$ is constant)','','The slope is 0','The slope is 1','The slope is ','A vertical line has no run (x = 0), so m = y/0 which is undefined. All points have the same x-coordinate.',10,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.806450','2026-01-05 16:56:59.806502',18),(154,'How do you find the **equation of a line** through two points $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$?','','1. Find slope: $m = \\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}$\n2. Use point-slope form: $y - y_1 = m(x - x_1)$\n3. Simplify','','Use the distance formula and solve for y','Average the points and use y = mx + c','Multiply the coordinates and divide by 2','First calculate the slope from the two points, then use either point with the point-slope formula.',11,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.807821','2026-01-05 16:56:59.807859',18),(155,'What is the formula for the **perpendicular distance** from point $(x_0, y_0)$ to line $ax + by + c = 0$?','','$d = \\frac{|ax_0 + by_0 + c|}{\\sqrt{a^2 + b^2}}$','','$d = \\frac{ax_0 + by_0 + c}{a^2 + b^2}$','$d = \\sqrt{(ax_0)^2 + (by_0)^2 + c^2}$','$d = |ax_0 + by_0 + c|$','This gives the shortest distance from a point to a line. The absolute value ensures distance is positive.',12,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.809701','2026-01-05 16:56:59.809751',18),(156,'How do you find where a line **intersects** the x-axis and y-axis?','','**x-intercept**: Set $y = 0$ and solve for $x$\n**y-intercept**: Set $x = 0$ and solve for $y$','','x-intercept: Set x = 0; y-intercept: Set y = 0','Use the distance formula from the origin','Find the midpoint of the line segment','Intercepts are where the line crosses the axes. At the x-axis, y = 0. At the y-axis, x = 0.',13,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.811082','2026-01-05 16:56:59.811125',18),(157,'In a right-angled triangle, what does **SOH CAH TOA** represent?','','SOH: sin  = Opposite/Hypotenuse\r\nCAH: cos  = Adjacent/Hypotenuse\r\nTOA: tan  = Opposite/Adjacent','','sin  = A/H, cos  = O/H, tan  = A/O','sin  = H/O, cos  = H/A, tan  = A/O','sin  = O/A, cos  = H/A, tan  = O/H','This mnemonic helps remember the three basic trigonometric ratios in right-angled triangles.',1,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.818378','2026-01-05 16:56:59.818422',19),(158,'How do you convert **degrees to radians**?','','Radians = Degrees  (/180)','','Radians = Degrees  180/','Radians = Degrees  2/180','Radians = Degrees $\\div$ 2/360','To convert from degrees to radians, multiply by /180. For example: 90 = 90  /180 = /2 radians.',8,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.819896','2026-01-05 16:56:59.819940',19),(159,'What is ** radians** in degrees?','','180','','90','360','270','Key conversions:  rad = 180, /2 rad = 90, /3 rad = 60, /4 rad = 45, /6 rad = 30.',9,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.821257','2026-01-05 16:56:59.821298',19),(160,'What is the formula for **arc length** $S$ of a circle with radius $r$ and angle $\\theta$ (in radians)?','','$S$ = $r$','','$S$ = $r$','$S$ = $r$','$S$ = $2r$','Arc length = radius  angle in radians. If angle is in degrees, convert to radians first.',10,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.822483','2026-01-05 16:56:59.822520',19),(161,'What is the formula for the **area of a sector** $A$ of a circle with radius $r$ and angle $\\theta$ (in radians)?','','$A$ = $(1/2)r$','','$A$ = $r$','$A$ = $r$','$A$ = $(1/2)r$','Sector area = (1/2)  radius  angle in radians. Compare to triangle area formula: (1/2)ab sin C.',11,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.823942','2026-01-05 16:56:59.823982',19),(162,'State the **Pythagorean identity** for sine and cosine.','','sin + cos = 1','','sin  + cos  = 1','sin - cos = 1','sin  cos = 1','This fundamental identity is true for all angles . It comes from Pythagoras\' theorem applied to the unit circle.',12,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.825323','2026-01-05 16:56:59.825366',19),(163,'Express **tan ** in terms of sin  and cos .','','tan  = sin  / cos ','','tan  = cos  / sin ','tan  = sin   cos ','tan  = 1 / (sin  cos )','This identity is useful for converting between trig functions. Also: 1 + tan = sec.',13,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.826450','2026-01-05 16:56:59.826485',19),(164,'What is the **period** of the function y = sin x?','','2 (or 360)','',' (or 180)','/2 (or 90)','4 (or 720)','The sine function repeats every 2 radians. For y = sin(bx), the period is 2/|b|.',18,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.827507','2026-01-05 16:56:59.827541',19),(165,'What is the **amplitude** of y = 3 sin x?','','3','','6','1','2','For y = A sin(bx), the amplitude is |A|. The graph oscillates between -3 and 3.',19,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.854028','2026-01-05 16:56:59.854055',19),(166,'What is the **period** of y = sin(2x)?','','','','2','/2','4','For y = sin(bx), period = 2/|b|. Here b = 2, so period = 2/2 = . The function completes two full cycles in 2.',20,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.854842','2026-01-05 16:56:59.854872',19),(167,'State **Pythagoras\' Theorem** for a right-angled triangle with hypotenuse c and other sides a and b.','','a + b = c','','a + b = c','a - b = c','a + b = 2c','In a right-angled triangle, the square of the hypotenuse equals the sum of the squares of the other two sides. This is fundamental for trigonometry and forms the basis for the Pythagorean identity sin + cos = 1.',21,'2026-01-05 16:56:59.855672','2026-01-05 16:56:59.855696',19);
