INSERT INTO `interactive_lessons_question` VALUES (1,1,0,'Descriptive Statistics - Definitions',NULL,'','','$$(3+4+5)/3$$',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Definitions',22,0,0),(2,1,1,'Descriptive Statistics - Mean',NULL,'','','From the following set of numbers, calculate the **mean** and the **mode**:  \r\n\r\n$3,\\ 12,\\ 17,\\ 24,\\ 24,\\ 31,\\ 34,\\ 39$\r\n\r\n**Solution:**  \r\n\r\nTo find the mean:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\dfrac{3 + 12 + 17 + 24 + 24 + 31 + 34 + 39}{8} = 23\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThe **mode** is the number that appears most often - **24**.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mean',28,0,0),(3,1,2,'Descriptive Statistics - Mean Median, Mode',NULL,'','','',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mean Median, Mode',29,0,0),(4,1,3,'Descriptive Statistics - Mean Mode Median',NULL,'','','We can rearrange the formula from Questions 1 and 2 to get:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Sum} = \\text{Mean} \\times \\text{Number of Numbers}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nWe know what our mean is, and we have 12 games, so there will be 12 numbers.\r\n\r\nThis means that:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Sum} = 21 \\times 12 = 252\r\n$$\r\n\r\nWhen we add up all the points scored by the team throughout the season we should get 252.\r\n\r\nWe can add the numbers we have together and add \\(x\\) for the value that we are trying to find.  \r\nWe know that they should equal 252, so with this equation we can solve for \\(x\\),  \r\nthe number of points scored in the 12\\textsuperscript{th} game.\r\n\r\n$$\r\n7 + 8 + 11 + 15 + 20 + 21 + 24 + 26 + 29 + 35 + 40 + x = 236 + x\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThis means that:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n236 + x = 252\r\n$$\r\n\r\nTo solve for \\(x\\), we can subtract 236 from both sides to give us:\r\n\r\n$$\r\nx = 16\r\n$$',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mean Mode Median',31,0,0),(5,1,4,'Descriptive Statistics - Mean Mode',NULL,'','','Add all the numbers:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n5 + 6 + 7 + 9 + 10 + 10 + 12 + 14 + 15 = 88\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThere are 9 numbers, so:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\frac{88}{9} \\approx 9.78\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThe mode is \\(10\\) because it appears more than once.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mean Mode',30,0,0),(6,1,5,'Descriptive Statistics - Mean Mode',NULL,'','','Add all the numbers:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n18 + 21 + 23 + 23 + 25 + 26 + 28 + 30 + 32 + 35 = 261\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThere are 10 numbers, so:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\frac{261}{10} = 26.1\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThe mode is \\(23\\) because it appears twice, more than any other number.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mean Mode',30,0,0),(7,1,6,'Descriptive Statistics - Mea Mode',NULL,'','','We use the formula:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Total Sum} = \\text{Mean} \\times \\text{Number of Scores}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo the total of all 15 students\' scores is:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n68 \\times 15 = 1020\r\n$$\r\n\r\nAdd the scores of the 14 known students:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n45 + 52 + 55 + 61 + 64 + 65 + 70 + 71 + 74 + 77 + 80 + 84 + 86 + 90 = 938\r\n$$\r\n\r\nNow subtract from the total to find the missing student\'s score:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n1020 - 938 = 82\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the 15th student scored 82.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Mea Mode',27,0,0),(8,1,7,'Descriptive Statistics - grouped-data questions',NULL,'','','Find the mid-interval values of all the intervals.  \r\nFor example, the mid-interval value of 20%-40% is 30%.  \r\n\r\nMultiply each mid-interval value by the frequency with which it occurs,  \r\nadd these products together, and divide by the total number of students.\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\frac{(10)(3) + (30)(6) + (50)(12) + (70)(14) + (90)(5)}{3 + 6 + 12 + 14 + 5}\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\frac{1680}{40} = 56\\\\%\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo the estimated mean score of students who took the exam is **56%**.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'grouped-data questions',40,0,0),(9,1,8,'Descriptive Statistics - grouped-data questions',NULL,'','','---\r\n  There are 40 students in total, so the median will be the 20$^{\\text{th}}$-21$^{\\text{st}}$ values.\r\n\r\n  Cumulative frequencies:\r\n\r\n  | Interval | Cumulative Frequency |\r\n  |----------|----------------------|\r\n  | 0%-20%   | 3                    |\r\n  | 20%-40%  | 9                    |\r\n  | 40%-60%  | 21                   |\r\n  | 60%-80%  | 35                   |\r\n  | 80%-100% | 40                   |\r\n\r\n  The 20$^{\\text{th}}$ and 21$^{\\text{st}}$ observations lie in the 40%-60% interval.\r\n\r\n  Therefore, the median interval is 40%-60%.\r\n\r\n  ---',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'grouped-data questions',40,0,0),(10,1,9,'Descriptive Statistics - grouped-data questions',NULL,'','','Find the mid-interval values and multiply each by its frequency.\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\frac{(5)(24) + (15)(18) + (25)(11) + (35)(13) + (45)(9) + (55)(5)}{24 + 18 + 11 + 13 + 9 + 5}\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Mean} = \\frac{1800}{80} = 22.5 \\text{ minutes}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo the estimated mean flight delay time is **22.5 minutes**.\r\n\r\nTo find the median interval, calculate cumulative frequencies:\r\n\r\n| Interval | Cumulative Frequency |\r\n|-----------|----------------------|\r\n| 0-10      | 24                   |\r\n\r\n| 10-20     | 42                   |\r\n| 20-30     | 53                   |\r\n| 30-40     | 66                   |\r\n| 40-50     | 75                   |\r\n| 50-60     | 80                   |\r\n\r\n---\r\n  The total number of flights is 80, so the median is the 40$^{\\text{th}}$-41$^{\\text{st}}$ values.These lie in the 10-20 interval.\r\n\r\n  ---\r\n\r\nTherefore, the **median interval is 10-20 minutes**.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'grouped-data questions',40,0,0),(11,1,10,'Descriptive Statistics - Range & Interquartile Range',NULL,'','','First, arrange the numbers in ascending order:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n3, 6, 7, 8, 14, 16, 18\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThe range is found by subtracting the smallest value from the largest value:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Range} = 18 - 3 = 15\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the range is **15**.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Range & Interquartile Range',33,0,0),(12,1,11,'Descriptive Statistics - Range & Interquartile Range',NULL,'','','Arrange the numbers in ascending order:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n3, 6, 7, 8, 14, 16, 18\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThere are \\(n = 7\\) values.\r\n\r\nTo find the quartile positions:\r\n\r\n$$\r\nQ_1 = \\frac{1}{4}(n + 1) = \\frac{1}{4}(8) = 2\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$$\r\nQ_3 = \\frac{3}{4}(n + 1) = \\frac{3}{4}(8) = 6\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThe 2nd value is \\(6\\), and the 6th value is \\(16\\).\r\n\r\nTherefore:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{IQR} = Q_3 - Q_1 = 16 - 6 = 10\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the interquartile range is **10**.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Range & Interquartile Range',33,0,0),(13,1,12,'Descriptive Statistics - Range & Interquartile Range',NULL,'','','Arrange the numbers in ascending order:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n1, 4, 6, 9, 11, 19, 20, 24, 26, 28\r\n$$\r\n\r\n**Range:**\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{Range} = 28 - 1 = 27\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThere are \\(n = 10\\) values.\r\n\r\nTo find the quartile positions:\r\n\r\n$$\r\nQ_1 = \\frac{1}{4}(n + 1) = \\frac{1}{4}(11) = 2.75\r\n$$\r\n\r\n$$\r\nQ_3 = \\frac{3}{4}(n + 1) = \\frac{3}{4}(11) = 8.25\r\n$$\r\n\r\nFor \\(Q_1 = 2.75\\), take the 2nd and 3rd terms (4 and 6):\r\n\r\n$$\r\nQ_1 = \\frac{4 + 6}{2} = 5\r\n$$\r\n\r\nFor \\(Q_3 = 8.25\\), take the 8th and 9th terms (24 and 26):\r\n\r\n$$\r\nQ_3 = \\frac{24 + 26}{2} = 25\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThen:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\text{IQR} = Q_3 - Q_1 = 25 - 5 = 20\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo,  \r\n**Range = 27**  \r\n**Interquartile Range = 20**',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Range & Interquartile Range',33,0,0),(14,1,13,'Descriptive Statistics - Standard Deviation',NULL,'','','To find the standard deviation, we use the formula:\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{n} \\sum (x - \\mu)^2}\r\n$$\r\nwhere each \\(x\\) is a value in the set, \\(\\mu\\) is the mean, and \\(n\\) is the number of values.\r\n\r\nFirst, find the mean:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\mu = \\frac{10 + 14 + 16 + 21 + 23}{5} = \\frac{84}{5} = 16.8\r\n$$\r\n\r\nNow find each \\((x - \\mu)^2\\):\r\n\r\n| \\(x\\) | \\(x - \\mu\\) | \\((x - \\mu)^2\\) |\r\n|-------|--------------|----------------|\r\n| 10 | -6.8 | 46.24 |\r\n| 14 | -2.8 | 7.84 |\r\n| 16 | -0.8 | 0.64 |\r\n| 21 | 4.2 | 17.64 |\r\n| 23 | 6.2 | 38.44 |\r\n\r\nAdd them up:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sum (x - \\mu)^2 = 46.24 + 7.84 + 0.64 + 17.64 + 38.44 = 110.8\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThen divide by \\(n = 5\\) and take the square root:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\frac{110.8}{5}} = \\sqrt{22.16} = 4.707\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the standard deviation is **4.707** (to 3 decimal places).\r\n\r\n---',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Standard Deviation',35,0,0),(15,1,14,'Descriptive Statistics - Standard Deviation',NULL,'','','Formula:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{n} \\sum (x - \\mu)^2}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nFirst, find the mean:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\mu = \\frac{8 + 12 + 19 + 27 + 33 + 34 + 36 + 36}{8} = \\frac{205}{8} = 25.625\r\n$$\r\n\r\nNow calculate each \\((x - \\mu)^2\\) and sum:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sum (x - \\mu)^2 = 882.75\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThen:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\frac{882.75}{8}} = \\sqrt{110.34} = 10.5\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the standard deviation is **10.5** (to 1 decimal place).',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Standard Deviation',35,0,0),(16,1,15,'Descriptive Statistics - Standard Deviation',NULL,'','','Formula:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{n} \\sum (x - \\mu)^2}\r\n$$\r\n\r\nFirst, find the mean:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\mu = \\frac{6 + 8 + 11 + 14 + 15 + 16 + 18 + 24 + 25 + 25 + 26 + 28 + 38 + 40}{14} = \\frac{294}{14} = 21\r\n$$\r\n\r\nNow compute:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sum (x - \\mu)^2 = 1378\r\n$$\r\n\r\nThen:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma = \\sqrt{\\frac{1378}{14}} = \\sqrt{98.43} = 9.9\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the standard deviation is **9.9** (to 1 decimal place).',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Standard Deviation',35,0,0),(17,1,16,'Descriptive Statistics - Standard Deviation using Calculator',NULL,'','','Input the numbers from set \\(A\\) into your calculator using the statistics function.\r\n\r\nThe calculator gives:\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\\sigma_A = 3.22\r\n$$\r\n\r\nSo, the standard deviation is **3.22**.',NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Standard Deviation using Calculator',36,0,0),(18,1,17,'Descriptive Statistics - Standard Deviation using a calculator',NULL,'','','Enter the data 