text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2}|x_1 y_2 - x_2 y_1|$$\n\nFor the general case (no vertex at origin), use the full formula.',NULL,155,1,0),(367,18,2,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Use your log tables\\!** For a triangle with vertices at $(x_1, y_1)$, $(x_2, y_2)$, and $(x_3, y_3)$, the area formula is:\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2}|x_1(y_2 - y_3) + x_2(y_3 - y_1) + x_3(y_1 - y_2)|$$\n\nTake the absolute value to ensure a positive area.',NULL,155,1,0),(368,18,3,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Use your log tables\\!** When one vertex is at the origin $(0, 0)$, use the simplified formula:\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2}|x_1 y_2 - x_2 y_1|$$\n\nThis is much easier than the general formula\\!',NULL,155,1,0),(369,18,4,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Use your log tables\\!** Choose the appropriate formula based on the vertices:\n- If one vertex is at origin: $\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2}|x_1 y_2 - x_2 y_1|$\n- General case: $\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2}|x_1(y_2 - y_3) + x_2(y_3 - y_1) + x_3(y_1 - y_2)|$',NULL,155,1,0),(374,18,1,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/intersection_q1_basic.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'To find where two lines intersect, solve the system of equations simultaneously. The solution $(x, y)$ represents the point of intersection. You can use substitution or elimination method.',NULL,156,1,0),(375,18,2,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/intersection_q2_standard.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'To find where two lines intersect, solve the system of equations simultaneously. You can solve one equation for a variable and substitute into the other.',NULL,156,1,0),(376,18,3,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/intersection_q3_roads.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'To find where two lines intersect, first derive the equations from the given points, then solve the system simultaneously.',NULL,156,1,0),(377,18,4,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/intersection_q4_cables.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'Derive the equations of both cable routes from the given points, then solve the system to find where