\log_b(a^y) = \\log_b x$\n\nUsing power rule: $y \\log_b a = \\log_b x$\n\nTherefore: $y = \\frac{\\log_b x}{\\log_b a}$',NULL,173,1,0),(451,10,1,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/composite_functions_q1.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'For exponential functions, remember that $e^{ax}$ grows rapidly as x increases. For logarithmic functions, use logarithm laws: $\\ln(x^n) = n\\ln(x)$. When solving $\\ln(x^2) = k$, rewrite as $2\\ln(x) = k$, so $\\ln(x) = \\frac{k}{2}$, giving $x = e^{k/2}$.',NULL,174,1,0),(452,10,2,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/composite_functions_q2.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'For exponential functions with base 10, remember that $10^{2x} = (10^2)^x = 100^x$. For logarithmic functions with coefficients inside the logarithm, use the property: $\\ln(kx) = \\ln(k) + \\ln(x)$. When solving $\\ln(5x) = k$, convert to exponential form: $5x = e^k$, so $x = \\frac{e^k}{5}$.',NULL,174,1,0),(453,10,3,NULL,NULL,'','solutions/composite_functions_q3.png',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'For exponential functions, $e^{ax}$ can be evaluated directly using a calculator. For logarithms involving roots, use the property: $\\ln(\\sqrt[n]{x}) = \\ln(x^{1/n}) = \\frac{1}{n}\\ln\\(x\\)$. When solving $\\ln(\\sqrt[3]{x}) = k$, rewrite as $\\frac{1}{3}\\ln\\(x\\) = k$, giving $\\ln\\(x\\) = 3k$, so $x = e^{3k}$.',NULL,174,1,0),(454,8,1005,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Hypothesis Testing for a Population Mean:**\n\nUse a **one-sample z-test** when:\n- Sample size is large ($n \\geq 30$)\n- Population standard deviation is unknown (use sample $s$)\n\n**Test Statistic:** $z = \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu_0}{s / \\sqrt{n}}$\n\nwhere $\\bar{x}$ = sample mean, $\\mu_0$ = claimed population mean, $s$ = sample standard deviation, $n$ = sample size\n\n**Decision Rule (5% significance, two-tailed):**\n- Reject $H_0$ if $|z| > 1.96$\n- Fail to reject $H_0$ if $|z| \\leq 1.96$',NULL,145,1,0),(455,8,455,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Hypothesis Testing for a Population Mean:**\n\nUse a **one-sample z-test** when:\n- Sample size is large ($n \\geq 30$)\n- Population standard deviation is unknown (use sample $s$)\n\n**Test Statistic:** $z = \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu_0}{s / \\sqrt{n}}$\n\nwhere $\\bar{x}$ = sample mean, $\\mu_0$ = claimed population mean, $s$ = sample standard deviation, $n$ = sample size\n\n**Decision Rule (5% significance, two-tailed):**\n- Reject $H_0$ if $|z| > 1.96$\n- Fail to reject $H_0$ if $|z| \\leq 1.96$',NULL,145,1,0),(456,8,456,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Hypothesis Testing for a Population Mean:**\n\nUse a **one-sample z-test** when:\n- Sample size is large ($n \\geq 30$)\n- Population standard deviation is unknown (use sample $s$)\n\n**Test Statistic:** $z = \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu_0}{s / \\sqrt{n}}$\n\nwhere $\\bar{x}$ = sample mean, $\\mu_0$ = claimed population mean, $s$ = sample standard deviation, $n$ = sample size\n\n**Decision Rule (5% significance, two-tailed):**\n- Reject $H_0$ if $|z| > 1.96$\n- Fail to reject $H_0$ if $|z| \\leq 1.96$',NULL,145,1,0),(457,8,1006,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'For hypothesis testing of proportions, use the test statistic:\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $p$ is the claimed population proportion  \n- $n$ is the sample size\n\nFor a two-tailed test at 5% significance, reject $H_0$ if $|z| > 1.96$.',NULL,146,1,0),(458,8,1007,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'For hypothesis testing of proportions, use the test statistic:\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $p$ is the claimed population proportion  \n- $n$ is the sample size\n\nFor a two-tailed test at 5% significance, reject $H_0$ if $|z| > 1.96$.',NULL,146,1,0),(459,8,1008,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'For hypothesis testing of proportions, use the test statistic:\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $p$ is the claimed population proportion  \n- $n$ is the sample size\n\nFor a **two-tailed** test at 5% significance, reject $H_0$ if $|z| > 1.96$.',NULL,146,1,0),(460,8,1009,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**P-value Method for Hypothesis Testing:**\n\nThe p-value is the probability of obtaining a test statistic as extreme as, or more extreme than, the observed value, assuming the null hypothesis is true.\n\nFor a two-tailed test: $p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times P(Z > |z|)$\n\n**Decision Rule:**\n- If p-value   (0.05), reject $H_0$\n- If p-value >  (0.05), fail to reject $H_0$\n\nThe smaller the p-value, the stronger the evidence against $H_0$.',NULL,147,1,0),(461,8,1010,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**P-value Method for Hypothesis Testing:**\n\nThe p-value is the probability of obtaining a test statistic as extreme as, or more extreme than, the observed value, assuming the null hypothesis is true.\n\nFor a two-tailed test: $p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times P(Z > |z|)$\n\n**Decision Rule:**\n- If p-value   (0.05), reject $H_0$\n- If p-value >  (0.05), fail to reject $H_0$\n\nThe smaller the p-value, the stronger the evidence against $H_0$.',NULL,147,1,0),(462,8,1011,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**P-value Method for Hypothesis Testing (Proportions):**\n\nThe p-value is the probability of obtaining a test statistic as extreme as, or more extreme than, the observed value, assuming the null hypothesis is true.\n\nFor a two-tailed test: $p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times P(Z > |z|)$\n\nwhere $z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$\n\n**Decision Rule:**\n- If p-value   (0.05), reject $H_0$\n- If p-value >  (0.05), fail to reject $H_0$',NULL,147,1,0),(463,8,1012,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Confidence Interval for a Proportion:**\n\n$$\\text{CI} = \\hat{p} \\pm z \\times \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $z$ is the critical value (1.96 for 95% confidence)\n- $n$ is the sample size\n\nThe margin of error is: $ME = z \\times \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}$',NULL,87,1,0),(464,8,1013,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,'**Confidence Interval for a Proportion:**\n\n$$\\text{CI} = \\hat{p} \\pm z \\times \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $z$ is the critical value (1.96 for 95% confidence)\n- $n$ is the sample size\n\nThe margin of error is: $ME = z \\times \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}$',NULL,87,1,0);
