$$\\frac{1}{4} + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$$\n$$\\cos^2 \\theta = 1 - \\frac{1}{4} = \\frac{3}{4}$$\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\pm \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$$\n\nFor the first quadrant, $\\cos \\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$\n\n**Step 3:** Calculate $\\tan \\theta$\n\n$$\\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = \\frac{\\frac{1}{2}}{\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}$$\n\n**Answer:** $\\cos \\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$, $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}$',0,'manual',NULL,5,208,'','',0),(267,'(a)','If $\\tan \\theta = 1$, find the value of $\\sin \\theta$.','$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$','Expression with square roots (can be rationalized or not)','**Step 1:** Use the identity $1 + \\tan^2 \\theta = \\sec^2 \\theta$\n\nSubstitute $\\tan \\theta = 1$:\n$$1 + 1^2 = \\sec^2 \\theta$$\n$$\\sec^2 \\theta = 2$$\n$$\\sec \\theta = \\sqrt{2}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Find $\\cos \\theta$\n\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sec \\theta} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Find $\\sin \\theta$ using $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta}$\n\n$$\\sin \\theta = \\tan \\theta \\cdot \\cos \\theta = 1 \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$$\n\n**Answer:** $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$',0,'manual',NULL,5,209,'','',0),(268,'(a)','Given that $\\sin A = 0.8$, find the value of $\\cos A$.','0.6','Decimal value','**Step 1:** Use the Pythagorean identity $\\sin^2 A + \\cos^2 A = 1$\n\nSubstitute $\\sin A = 0.8$:\n$$(0.8)^2 + \\cos^2 A = 1$$\n\n**Step 2:** Solve for $\\cos A$\n\n$$0.64 + \\cos^2 A = 1$$\n$$\\cos^2 A = 1 - 0.64 = 0.36$$\n$$\\cos A = \\pm 0.6$$\n\nFor the first quadrant, $\\cos A = 0.6$\n\n**Answer:** $\\cos A = 0.6$',0,'numeric',NULL,5,210,'','',0),(269,'(a)','Find the area of the triangle below.','30','Integer value in cm','**Step 1:** Identify the base and height\n\nThe triangle has a right angle (marked with a square). The two sides forming the right angle are:\n- Base = 5 cm\n- Height = 12 cm\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the area formula\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text{base} \\times \\text{height}$$\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 5 \\times 12$$\n\n**Step 3:** Calculate\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 60 = 30 \\text{ cm}^2$$\n\n**Answer:** 30 cm',0,'numeric',NULL,5,211,'question_part_images/triangle_area_5_12_13_K3l5xbW.png','',0),(270,'(a)','Find the area of the following right-angled triangle.','24','Integer value in cm','**Step 1:** Find the base using Pythagoras theorem\n\nThe triangle has:\n- Height = 6 cm\n- Hypotenuse = 10 cm\n- Base = unknown\n\nUsing Pythagoras: $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$\n\n$$6^2 + b^2 = 10^2$$\n$$36 + b^2 = 100$$\n$$b^2 = 64$$\n$$b = 8 \\text{ cm}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the area formula\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text{base} \\times \\text{height}$$\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 8 \\times 6$$\n\n**Step 3:** Calculate\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 48 = 24 \\text{ cm}^2$$\n\n**Answer:** 24 cm',0,'numeric',NULL,5,212,'question_part_images/triangle_area_6_8_10_srZwdUo.png','',0),(271,'(a)','Find the area of $\\triangle ABC$.','$2\\sqrt{2}$','Expression with square root','**Step 1:** Find the base BC using Pythagoras theorem\n\nThe triangle has:\n- AB (height) = 2 cm\n- AC (hypotenuse) = $2\\sqrt{3}$ cm\n- BC (base) = unknown\n\nUsing Pythagoras: $AB^2 + BC^2 = AC^2$\n\n$$2^2 + BC^2 = (2\\sqrt{3})^2$$\n$$4 + BC^2 = 4 \\times 3$$\n$$4 + BC^2 = 12$$\n$$BC^2 = 8$$\n$$BC = 2\\sqrt{2} \\text{ cm}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Calculate the area\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text{base} \\times \\text{height}$$\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 2\\sqrt{2} \\times 2$$\n\n$$\\text{Area} = 2\\sqrt{2} \\text{ cm}^2$$\n\n**Answer:** $2\\sqrt{2}$ cm',0,'expression',NULL,5,213,'question_part_images/triangle_ABC_2_2sqrt3_3pVHmKj.png','',0),(272,'(b)','Find the length of the shortest distance from the point $B$ to the line $AC$.','$\\frac{2\\sqrt{6}}{3}$','Expression with square root (fraction form)','**Step 1:** Understand what we are finding\n\nThe shortest distance from point B to line AC is the perpendicular height from B to AC. We can use the area formula rearranged:\n\n$$\\text{Area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\text{base} \\times \\text{perpendicular height}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Use the area from part (a)\n\nFrom part (a), we know:\n- Area = $2\\sqrt{2}$ cm\n- Base AC = $2\\sqrt{3}$ cm\n\nRearranging for perpendicular height:\n\n$$\\text{perpendicular height} = \\frac{2 \\times \\text{Area}}{\\text{base}}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Calculate\n\n$$h = \\frac{2 \\times 2\\sqrt{2}}{2\\sqrt{3}}$$\n\n$$h = \\frac{4\\sqrt{2}}{2\\sqrt{3}}$$\n\n$$h = \\frac{2\\sqrt{2}}{\\sqrt{3}}$$\n\n**Step 4:** Rationalize the denominator\n\n$$h = \\frac{2\\sqrt{2}}{\\sqrt{3}} \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}}$$\n\n$$h = \\frac{2\\sqrt{6}}{3} \\text{ cm}$$\n\n**Answer:** $\\frac{2\\sqrt{6}}{3}$ cm',1,'expression',NULL,5,213,'question_part_images/triangle_ABC_2_2sqrt3_3pVHmKj_IGQ2eLg.png','',0),(273,'(a)','Find, correct to two decimal places, the value of $x$.','7.32','Decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Identify the known values\n\nWe have a triangle with:\n- Angle at bottom left = 75\n- Angle at top right = 60\n- Angle at top = 45\n- Side opposite 75 angle = 10\n- Side opposite 45 angle = $x$ (unknown)\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the Sine Rule\n\n$$\\frac{x}{\\sin 45} = \\frac{10}{\\sin 75}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for x\n\n$$x = \\frac{10 \\times \\sin 45}{\\sin 75}$$\n\n$$x = \\frac{10 \\times 0.7071}{0.9659}$$\n\n$$x = 7.32 \\text{ (to 2 decimal places)}$$\n\n**Answer:** 7.32',0,'numeric',NULL,5,214,'question_part_images/sine_rule_find_x_45_60_75_EpeTQ5V.png','',0),(274,'(a)','Find, correct to two decimal places, the value of $y$.','6.35','Decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Identify the known values\n\nWe have a triangle with:\n- Angle at top = 75\n- Angle at bottom right = 50\n- Angle at bottom left = 55 (180 - 75 - 50)\n- Base (opposite 75 angle) = 8\n- Side $y$ opposite 50 angle = unknown\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the Sine Rule\n\n$$\\frac{y}{\\sin 50} = \\frac{8}{\\sin 75}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for y\n\n$$y = \\frac{8 \\times \\sin 50}{\\sin 75}$$\n\n$$y = \\frac{8 \\times 0.7660}{0.9659}$$\n\n$$y = 6.35 \\text{ (to 2 decimal places)}$$\n\n**Answer:** 6.35',0,'numeric',NULL,5,215,'question_part_images/sine_rule_find_y_75_50_XZhI1ws.png','',0),(275,'(a)','In the diagram below, the points $A, B, C$ are collinear. If $|AB| = 7$, $|\\angle BAD| = 35$, $|\\angle ABD| = 60$, and $|\\angle BCD| = 25$, find, correct to two decimal places: $w$','4.03','Decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Find the third angle in triangle ABD\n\nIn triangle ABD:\n- $\\angle BAD = 35$\n- $\\angle ABD = 60$\n- $\\angle ADB = 180 - 35 - 60 = 85$\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the Sine Rule to triangle ABD\n\nIn the diagram, $w$ represents side BD.\n\n$$\\frac{w}{\\sin(\\angle BAD)} = \\frac{AB}{\\sin(\\angle ADB)}$$\n\n$$\\frac{w}{\\sin 35} = \\frac{7}{\\sin 85}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for w\n\n$$w = \\frac{7 \\times \\sin 35}{\\sin 85}$$\n\n$$w = \\frac{7 \\times 0.5736}{0.9962}$$\n\n$$w = 4.03 \\text{ (to 2 decimal places)}$$\n\n**Answer:** 4.03',0,'numeric',NULL,5,216,'question_part_images/sine_rule_collinear_final_v2.png','',0),(276,'(b)','In the diagram below, the points $A, B, C$ are collinear. If $|AB| = 7$, $|\\angle BAD| = 35$, $|\\angle ABD| = 60$, and $|\\angle BCD| = 25$, find, correct to two decimal places: $z$','8.26','Decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Find side BD from triangle ABD\n\nUsing the Sine Rule in triangle ABD:\n\n$$\\frac{BD}{\\sin(\\angle BAD)} = \\frac{AB}{\\sin(\\angle ADB)}$$\n\n$$\\frac{BD}{\\sin 35} = \\frac{7}{\\sin 85}$$\n\n$$BD = \\frac{7 \\times \\sin 35}{\\sin 85} = 4.03$$\n\n**Step 2:** Find angle DBC\n\nSince points A, B, C are collinear:\n- $\\angle ABC = 180$ (straight line)\n- $\\angle ABD = 60$ (given)\n- Therefore: $\\angle DBC = 180 - 60 = 120$\n\n**Step 3:** Find the third angle in triangle BCD\n\nIn triangle BCD:\n- $\\angle DBC = 120$\n- $\\angle BCD = 25$\n- $\\angle BDC = 180 - 120 - 25 = 35$\n\n**Step 4:** Apply Sine Rule to triangle BCD to find z\n\nIn triangle BCD, $z$ represents side CD.\n\n$$\\frac{CD}{\\sin(\\angle DBC)} = \\frac{BD}{\\sin(\\angle BCD)}$$\n\n$$\\frac{z}{\\sin 120} = \\frac{4.03}{\\sin 25}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{4.03 \\times \\sin 120}{\\sin 25}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{4.03 \\times 0.8660}{0.4226}$$\n\n$$z = 8.26 \\text{ (to 2 decimal places)}$$\n\n**Answer:** 8.26',1,'numeric',NULL,5,216,'question_part_images/sine_rule_collinear_final_v2_kKh9Rb1.png','',0),(277,'(a)','In $\\triangle ABC$, $|AC| = 5$, $|AB| = 7$ and $|\\angle ABC| = 35$.\n\nSketch a diagram of the two triangles that satisfy these conditions.','See solution diagram','Diagram sketch showing both possible triangles','The ambiguous case occurs because we have SSA (Side-Side-Angle) information.\n\nGiven: $|AB| = 7$, $|\\angle ABC| = 35$, $|AC| = 5$\n\nThe two possible triangles are $\\triangle ABC$ and $\\triangle ABC\'$ as shown in the diagram.',0,'manual',NULL,5,217,'','solutions/ambiguous_case_two_triangles.png',0),(278,'(b)','For the triangles in Question 1, find the two possible values of $|\\angle ACB|$, correct to the nearest degree.','53 and 127','Two integer values in degrees','**Step 1:** Using the diagram from Question 1, consider the triangle on the LHS and work to find the angle marked $\\theta$. Apply the Sine Rule:\n\n$$\\frac{7}{\\sin \\theta} = \\frac{5}{\\sin 35}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Rearrange to solve for $\\sin \\theta$:\n\n$$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{7 \\sin 35}{5}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Calculate the first angle:\n\n$$\\theta = \\sin^{-1}\\left(\\frac{7 \\sin 35}{5}\\right) \\approx 53$$\n\n**Step 4:** Find the second possible value (ambiguous case of the Sine Rule). Since $\\sin \\theta = \\sin(180 - \\theta)$:\n\n$$\\theta_2 = 180 - 53 = 127$$\n\n**Answer:** 53 and 127',1,'manual',NULL,10,217,'','',0),(279,'(a)','In $\\triangle XYZ$, $|XY| = 4$ cm, $|XZ| = 2$ cm, and $|\\angle XYZ| = 25$. Find, correct to two decimal places, the two possible values of $|\\angle XZY|$.','57.69 and 122.31','Two decimal values in degrees to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Apply the Sine Rule to find $|\\angle XZY|$. Let $|\\angle XZY| = \\theta$.\r\n\r\n$$\\frac{|XY|}{\\sin \\theta} = \\frac{|XZ|}{\\sin 25}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Substitute the known values:\r\n\r\n$$\\frac{4}{\\sin \\theta} = \\frac{2}{\\sin 25}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Rearrange to solve for $\\sin \\theta$:\r\n\r\n$$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{4 \\sin 25}{2} = 2 \\sin 25$$\r\n\r\n$$\\sin \\theta \\approx 2 \\times 0.4226 = 0.8452$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Find the first angle:\r\n\r\n$$\\theta_1 = \\sin^{-1}(0.8452) \\approx 57.69$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Find the second possible value (ambiguous case):\r\n\r\n$$\\theta_2 = 180 - 57.69 = 122.31$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 57.69 and 122.31',0,'manual',NULL,10,218,'','solutions/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_11.07.48.png',0),(280,'(a)','Find the area of the triangle below.\r\n\r\n[Triangle with sides 6 cm and 8 cm, with included angle 60]','12*sqrt(3)','Exact answer in surd form or decimal equivalent','**Step 1:** Identify the formula for the area of a triangle with two sides and the included angle:\r\n\r\n$$A = \\frac{1}{2}ab\\sin C$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Identify the values: $a = 6$ cm, $b = 8$ cm, and $C = 60$.\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute into the formula:\r\n\r\n$$A = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 6 \\times 8 \\times \\sin 60$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate (note that $\\sin 60 = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$):\r\n\r\n$$A = 24 \\times \\sin 60 = 24 \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} = 12\\sqrt{3}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Express as a decimal if needed:\r\n\r\n$$A = 12\\sqrt{3} \\approx 20.78 \\text{ cm}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** $12\\sqrt{3}$ cm or 20.78 cm',0,'expression',NULL,5,219,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_11.14.20.png','solutions/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_11.14.20.png',0),(281,'(a)','Find, correct to the nearest whole number, the area of the triangle below.\r\n\r\n[Triangle with base 12, sides 13.4 and 9.8, angles 45, 60, and 75]','57','Integer value (whole number)','**Step 1:** Identify the formula for the area of a triangle with two sides and the included angle:\r\n\r\n$$A = \\frac{1}{2}ab\\sin C$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Choose two sides and their included angle. Using the base (12) and left side (13.4) with the included angle 45:\r\n\r\n$$A = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 12 \\times 13.4 \\times \\sin 45$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Evaluate (note that $\\sin 45 = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} \\approx 0.7071$):\r\n\r\n$$A = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 12 \\times 13.4 \\times 0.7071$$\r\n\r\n$$A = 80.4 \\times 0.7071 \\approx 56.85 \\text{ cm}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Round to the nearest whole number:\r\n\r\n$$A \\approx 57 \\text{ cm}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 57 cm',0,'numeric',NULL,5,220,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_11.17.17.png','',0),(282,'(a)','The triangles below have the same area. Find, correct to two decimal places, the value of $x$.\r\n\r\n[Two triangles: Triangle 1 with base $(x+2)$ cm, side $x$ cm, angle 30; Triangle 2 with sides 12 cm, 10 cm, and $2\\sqrt{91}$ cm, angle 120]','13.45','Decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Find the area of the first triangle using $A = \\frac{1}{2}ab\\sin C$:\r\n\r\n$$A_1 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times (x+2) \\times x \\times \\sin 30$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Simplify (note that $\\sin 30 = 0.5$):\r\n\r\n$$A_1 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times (x+2) \\times x \\times 0.5 = \\frac{x(x+2)}{4}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Find the area of the second triangle:\r\n\r\n$$A_2 = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 12 \\times 10 \\times \\sin 120$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Simplify (note that $\\sin 120 = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\approx 0.8660$):\r\n\r\n$$A_2 = 60 \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} = 30\\sqrt{3} \\approx 51.96$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Since the areas are equal, set $A_1 = A_2$:\r\n\r\n$$\\frac{x(x+2)}{4} = 30\\sqrt{3}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Solve for $x$:\r\n\r\n$$x(x+2) = 120\\sqrt{3}$$\r\n\r\n$$x^2 + 2x = 120\\sqrt{3} \\approx 207.85$$\r\n\r\n$$x^2 + 2x - 207.85 = 0$$\r\n\r\n**Step 7:** Use the quadratic formula: $x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$\r\n\r\n$$x = \\frac{-2 \\pm \\sqrt{4 + 831.38}}{2} = \\frac{-2 \\pm \\sqrt{835.38}}{2}$$\r\n\r\n$$x = \\frac{-2 \\pm 28.90}{2}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 8:** Take the positive solution:\r\n\r\n$$x = \\frac{26.90}{2} = 13.45$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 13.45 cm',0,'numeric',NULL,10,221,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_11.19.53.png','',0),(283,'(a)','Find $|AC|$.\r\n\r\n[Triangle ABC with $|AB| = 7$, $|BC| = 5$, and $\\angle ABC = 120$]','sqrt(109)','Exact answer in surd form or decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Identify the given information:\r\n- $|AB| = 7$\r\n- $|BC| = 5$\r\n- $\\angle ABC = 120$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find $|AC|$:\r\n\r\n$$|AC|^2 = |AB|^2 + |BC|^2 - 2|AB||BC|\\cos(\\angle ABC)$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values:\r\n\r\n$$|AC|^2 = 7^2 + 5^2 - 2(7)(5)\\cos 120$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate (note that $\\cos 120 = -0.5$):\r\n\r\n$$|AC|^2 = 49 + 25 - 70 \\times (-0.5)$$\r\n\r\n$$|AC|^2 = 74 + 35 = 109$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Take the square root:\r\n\r\n$$|AC| = \\sqrt{109}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Express as a decimal if needed:\r\n\r\n$$|AC| \\approx 10.44$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** $\\sqrt{109}$ or 10.44',0,'expression',NULL,5,222,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.39.48.png','',0),(284,'(a)','Find, correct to one decimal place, the length of the side marked $x$.\r\n\r\n[Triangle with sides $3\\sqrt{5}$ and $2\\sqrt{3}$, with included angle 40, opposite side marked $x$]','4.6','Decimal to 1 decimal place','**Step 1:** Identify the given information:\r\n- Side 1 = $3\\sqrt{5}$\r\n- Side 2 = $2\\sqrt{3}$\r\n- Included angle = $40$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find $x$:\r\n\r\n$$x^2 = (3\\sqrt{5})^2 + (2\\sqrt{3})^2 - 2(3\\sqrt{5})(2\\sqrt{3})\\cos 40$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Evaluate the squared terms:\r\n\r\n$$x^2 = 9 \\times 5 + 4 \\times 3 - 2(3\\sqrt{5})(2\\sqrt{3})\\cos 40$$\r\n\r\n$$x^2 = 45 + 12 - 12\\sqrt{15}\\cos 40$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate (note that $\\sqrt{15} \\approx 3.873$ and $\\cos 40 \\approx 0.7660$):\r\n\r\n$$x^2 = 57 - 12 \\times 3.873 \\times 0.7660$$\r\n\r\n$$x^2 = 57 - 35.59 = 21.41$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Take the square root:\r\n\r\n$$x = \\sqrt{21.41} \\approx 4.627$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Round to one decimal place:\r\n\r\n$$x \\approx 4.6$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 4.6',0,'numeric',NULL,5,223,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.42.05.png','',0),(285,'(a)','Find, correct to the nearest whole number, the length of the side marked $y$.\r\n\r\n[Triangle with sides 16.5 and 10, with included angle 45, opposite side marked $y$]','12','Integer value (whole number)','**Step 1:** Identify the given information:\r\n- Side 1 = 16.5\r\n- Side 2 = 10\r\n- Included angle = $45$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find $y$:\r\n\r\n$$y^2 = 16.5^2 + 10^2 - 2(16.5)(10)\\cos 45$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Evaluate:\r\n\r\n$$y^2 = 272.25 + 100 - 330\\cos 45$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Calculate (note that $\\cos 45 = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} \\approx 0.7071$):\r\n\r\n$$y^2 = 372.25 - 330 \\times 0.7071$$\r\n\r\n$$y^2 = 372.25 - 233.34 = 138.91$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Take the square root:\r\n\r\n$$y = \\sqrt{138.91} \\approx 11.79$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Round to the nearest whole number:\r\n\r\n$$y \\approx 12$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 12',0,'numeric',NULL,5,224,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.43.33.png','',0),(286,'(a)','Find, correct to the nearest degree, the size of the angle $\\theta$.\r\n\r\n[Triangle with sides 2, 4, and 5, with angle $\\theta$ opposite the side of length 4]','49','Integer value in degrees','**Step 1:** Identify the given information:\r\n- Side opposite $\\theta$ = 4\r\n- Other two sides = 2 and 5\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find $\\theta$:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{a^2 + b^2 - c^2}{2ab}$$\r\n\r\nwhere $a = 2$, $b = 5$, and $c = 4$ (opposite to $\\theta$).\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{2^2 + 5^2 - 4^2}{2(2)(5)}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{4 + 25 - 16}{20} = \\frac{13}{20} = 0.65$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Find the angle:\r\n\r\n$$\\theta = \\cos^{-1}(0.65) \\approx 49.46$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Round to the nearest degree:\r\n\r\n$$\\theta \\approx 49$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 49',0,'numeric',NULL,5,225,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.51.11.png','',0),(287,'(a)','Find, correct to two decimal places, the size of the angle $\\theta$.\r\n\r\n[Triangle with sides 10, 12, and 5, with angle $\\theta$ opposite the side of length 5]','24.10','Decimal to 2 decimal places in degrees','**Step 1:** Identify the given information:\r\n- Side opposite $\\theta$ = 5\r\n- Other two sides = 10 and 12\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find $\\theta$:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{a^2 + b^2 - c^2}{2ab}$$\r\n\r\nwhere $a = 10$, $b = 12$, and $c = 5$ (opposite to $\\theta$).\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{10^2 + 12^2 - 5^2}{2(10)(12)}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{100 + 144 - 25}{240} = \\frac{219}{240} = 0.9125$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Find the angle:\r\n\r\n$$\\theta = \\cos^{-1}(0.9125) \\approx 24.10$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 24.10',0,'numeric',NULL,5,226,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.53.46.png','',0),(288,'(a)','A triangle has sides of length 30, 25 and 10 cm. Find the size of the largest angle in the triangle, correct to two decimal places.','110.49','Decimal to 2 decimal places in degrees','**Step 1:** Identify which angle is the largest. The largest angle is opposite the longest side.\r\n\r\nLongest side = 30 cm, so we need to find the angle opposite this side.\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find the largest angle:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{a^2 + b^2 - c^2}{2ab}$$\r\n\r\nwhere $a = 25$, $b = 10$, and $c = 30$ (the longest side).\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{25^2 + 10^2 - 30^2}{2(25)(10)}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos \\theta = \\frac{625 + 100 - 900}{500} = \\frac{-175}{500} = -0.35$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Find the angle (note that the negative cosine indicates an obtuse angle):\r\n\r\n$$\\theta = \\cos^{-1}(-0.35) \\approx 110.49$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 110.49',0,'numeric',NULL,5,227,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.54.52.png','',0),(289,'(a)','Find $|AB|$.\r\n\r\n[3D diagram showing triangles ABC and BCD with BC = 10m vertical, angle CAB = 60, angle BDC = 30]','(10*sqrt(3))/3','Exact surd form or decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Identify that triangle ABC is right-angled at B with $|BC| = 10$ m and $\\angle CAB = 60$.\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Use the tangent ratio:\r\n\r\n$$\\tan 60 = \\frac{|BC|}{|AB|}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Rearrange to solve for $|AB|$:\r\n\r\n$$|AB| = \\frac{|BC|}{\\tan 60} = \\frac{10}{\\sqrt{3}}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Rationalize the denominator:\r\n\r\n$$|AB| = \\frac{10}{\\sqrt{3}} \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{10\\sqrt{3}}{3}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Express as decimal if needed:\r\n\r\n$$|AB| \\approx 5.77 \\text{ m}$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** $\\frac{10\\sqrt{3}}{3}$ m or 5.77 m',0,'expression',NULL,5,228,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_16.58.38.png','',0),(290,'(b)','Find $|BD|$.','10*sqrt(3)','Exact surd form or decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** Identify that triangle BCD is right-angled at B with $|BC| = 10$ m and $\\angle BDC = 30$.\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Use the tangent ratio:\r\n\r\n$$\\tan 30 = \\frac{|BC|}{|BD|}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Rearrange to solve for $|BD|$:\r\n\r\n$$|BD| = \\frac{|BC|}{\\tan 30} = \\frac{10}{1/\\sqrt{3}} = 10\\sqrt{3}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Express as decimal if needed:\r\n\r\n$$|BD| \\approx 17.32 \\text{ m}$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** $10\\sqrt{3}$ m or 17.32 m',1,'expression',NULL,5,228,'','',0),(291,'(c)','If $|\\angle ABD| = 120$, find $|AD|$.','(10*sqrt(39))/3','Exact surd form or decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** We now have triangle ABD with:\r\n- $|AB| = \\frac{10\\sqrt{3}}{3}$ m (from part a)\r\n- $|BD| = 10\\sqrt{3}$ m (from part b)\r\n- $\\angle ABD = 120$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule:\r\n\r\n$$|AD|^2 = |AB|^2 + |BD|^2 - 2|AB||BD|\\cos 120$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute values (note that $\\cos 120 = -0.5$):\r\n\r\n$$|AD|^2 = \\left(\\frac{10\\sqrt{3}}{3}\\right)^2 + (10\\sqrt{3})^2 - 2\\left(\\frac{10\\sqrt{3}}{3}\\right)(10\\sqrt{3})(-0.5)$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Evaluate:\r\n\r\n$$|AD|^2 = \\frac{300}{9} + 300 + \\frac{300}{3}$$\r\n\r\n$$|AD|^2 = \\frac{100}{3} + 300 + 100 = \\frac{1300}{3}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Take the square root and simplify:\r\n\r\n$$|AD| = \\sqrt{\\frac{1300}{3}} = \\frac{10\\sqrt{13}}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{10\\sqrt{39}}{3}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Express as decimal:\r\n\r\n$$|AD| \\approx 20.82 \\text{ m}$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** $\\frac{10\\sqrt{39}}{3}$ m or 20.82 m',2,'expression',NULL,10,228,'','',0),(292,'(a)','In the square-based pyramid below $|AB| = |AC| = |AD| = |AE| = 10$ cm and $|BC| = 8$ cm.\r\n\r\nFind $|\\angle ADE|$, correct to two decimal places.\r\n\r\n[Square-based pyramid with apex A, square base BCDE, center B, all slant edges 10 cm, base edge 8 cm]','66.42','Decimal to 2 decimal places in degrees','**Step 1:** Identify triangle ADE where:\r\n- $|AD| = |AE| = 10$ cm (slant edges)\r\n- $|DE| = 8$ cm (side of square base)\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Apply the Cosine Rule to find $\\angle ADE$:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos(\\angle ADE) = \\frac{|AD|^2 + |DE|^2 - |AE|^2}{2|AD||DE|}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute values:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos(\\angle ADE) = \\frac{10^2 + 8^2 - 10^2}{2(10)(8)} = \\frac{100 + 64 - 100}{160} = \\frac{64}{160} = 0.4$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Find the angle:\r\n\r\n$$\\angle ADE = \\cos^{-1}(0.4) \\approx 66.42$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 66.42',0,'numeric',NULL,5,229,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_17.03.01.png','',0),(293,'(b)','Find the total surface area of the pyramid, including the base, correct to the nearest m.','211','Integer value (whole number in m)','**Step 1:** Calculate the area of the square base:\r\n\r\n$$\\text{Base area} = 8^2 = 64 \\text{ cm}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Calculate the area of one triangular face. Each face is an isosceles triangle with base 8 cm and two equal sides of 10 cm.\r\n\r\nFind the perpendicular height of the triangle using Pythagoras (height bisects the base):\r\n\r\n$$h^2 + 4^2 = 10^2$$\r\n$$h^2 = 100 - 16 = 84$$\r\n$$h = \\sqrt{84} = 2\\sqrt{21}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Area of one triangular face:\r\n\r\n$$\\text{Triangle area} = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 8 \\times 2\\sqrt{21} = 8\\sqrt{21} \\text{ cm}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Total surface area (base + 4 triangular faces):\r\n\r\n$$\\text{Total area} = 64 + 4(8\\sqrt{21}) = 64 + 32\\sqrt{21}$$\r\n\r\n$$\\text{Total area} \\approx 64 + 146.64 = 210.64 \\text{ cm}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Round to nearest m:\r\n\r\n$$\\text{Total area} \\approx 211 \\text{ m}^2$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 211 m',1,'numeric',NULL,10,229,'','',0),(294,'(c)','Find the perpendicular height of the pyramid, i.e the shortest distance from the apex $A$ to the square base.','2*sqrt(17)','Exact surd form or decimal to 2 decimal places','**Step 1:** The perpendicular height goes from apex A to center B of the square base. First, find the distance from B to a corner (half the diagonal).\r\n\r\nDiagonal of square base:\r\n\r\n$$\\text{Diagonal} = 8\\sqrt{2} \\text{ cm}$$\r\n\r\nHalf diagonal (from center B to corner D):\r\n\r\n$$|BD| = 4\\sqrt{2} \\text{ cm}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Use Pythagoras theorem in the right-angled triangle ABD (right angle at B):\r\n\r\n$$|AB|^2 + |BD|^2 = |AD|^2$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Substitute values:\r\n\r\n$$|AB|^2 + (4\\sqrt{2})^2 = 10^2$$\r\n\r\n$$|AB|^2 + 32 = 100$$\r\n\r\n$$|AB|^2 = 68$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Solve for the perpendicular height:\r\n\r\n$$|AB| = \\sqrt{68} = \\sqrt{4 \\times 17} = 2\\sqrt{17}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Express as decimal if needed:\r\n\r\n$$|AB| \\approx 8.25 \\text{ cm}$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** $2\\sqrt{17}$ cm or 8.25 cm',2,'expression',NULL,10,229,'','',0),(295,'(a)','Consider the rectangular block below. Find $|\\angle AFC|$, correct to the nearest degree.\r\n\r\n[Rectangular block with length 20 cm, width 10 cm, height 5 cm. Vertices labeled A-H, with diagonal AF marked]','77','Integer value in degrees','**Step 1:** Find $|AC|$, the diagonal of the base rectangle ABCD.\r\n\r\nUsing Pythagoras:\r\n\r\n$$|AC|^2 = |AD|^2 + |DC|^2 = 20^2 + 10^2 = 400 + 100 = 500$$\r\n\r\n$$|AC| = \\sqrt{500} = 10\\sqrt{5} \\text{ cm}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 2:** Find $|AF|$, the space diagonal from A to F.\r\n\r\nUsing Pythagoras with the base diagonal and height:\r\n\r\n$$|AF|^2 = |AC|^2 + |CF|^2 = 500 + 5^2 = 525$$\r\n\r\n$$|AF| = \\sqrt{525} = 5\\sqrt{21} \\text{ cm}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 3:** Identify $|FC|$, which is the vertical edge:\r\n\r\n$$|FC| = 5 \\text{ cm}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 4:** Apply the Cosine Rule in triangle AFC:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos(\\angle AFC) = \\frac{|AF|^2 + |FC|^2 - |AC|^2}{2|AF||FC|}$$\r\n\r\n**Step 5:** Substitute values:\r\n\r\n$$\\cos(\\angle AFC) = \\frac{525 + 25 - 500}{2\\sqrt{525} \\times 5} = \\frac{50}{10\\sqrt{525}}$$\r\n\r\n$$\\cos(\\angle AFC) = \\frac{5}{\\sqrt{525}} = \\frac{5}{5\\sqrt{21}} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{21}} \\approx 0.218$$\r\n\r\n**Step 6:** Find the angle:\r\n\r\n$$\\angle AFC = \\cos^{-1}(0.218) \\approx 77.40$$\r\n\r\n**Step 7:** Round to nearest degree:\r\n\r\n$$\\angle AFC \\approx 77$$\r\n\r\n**Answer:** 77',0,'numeric',NULL,10,230,'question_part_images/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_17.06.36.png','solutions/Screenshot_2025-11-23_at_17.11.27.png',0),(296,'(a)','Using the table on page 13 of the Formulae and Tables Book, express $\\sin 150$ in surd form.','1/2','Exact fraction or surd form','**Step 1:** Recognize that $150 = 180 - 30$.\n\n**Step 2:** Use the sine symmetry property:\n\n$$\\sin(180 - \\theta) = \\sin \\theta$$\n\nTherefore:\n\n$$\\sin 150 = \\sin(180 - 30) = \\sin 30$$\n\n**Step 3:** From the Formulae and Tables Book (or standard exact values):\n\n$$\\sin 30 = \\frac{1}{2}$$\n\n**Answer:** $\\frac{1}{2}$',0,'expression',NULL,5,231,'','',0),(297,'(a)','Using the table on page 13 of the Formulae and Tables Book, express $\\cos 315$ in surd form.','sqrt(2)/2','Exact fraction or surd form','**Step 1:** Recognize that $315 = 360 - 45$.\n\n**Step 2:** Use the cosine symmetry property:\n\n$$\\cos(360 - \\theta) = \\cos \\theta$$\n\nTherefore:\n\n$$\\cos 315 = \\cos(360 - 45) = \\cos 45$$\n\n**Step 3:** From the Formulae and Tables Book (or standard exact values):\n\n$$\\cos 45 = \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$$\n\n**Answer:** $\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}$',0,'expression',NULL,5,232,'','',0),(298,'(a)','Using the table on page 13 of the Formulae and Tables Book, express $\\tan 120$ in surd form.','-sqrt(3)','Exact surd form','**Step 1:** Recognize that $120 = 180 - 60$.\n\n**Step 2:** Use the tangent symmetry property:\n\n$$\\tan(180 - \\theta) = -\\tan \\theta$$\n\nTherefore:\n\n$$\\tan 120 = \\tan(180 - 60) = -\\tan 60$$\n\n**Step 3:** From the Formulae and Tables Book (or standard exact values):\n\n$$\\tan 60 = \\sqrt{3}$$\n\n**Step 4:** Apply the negative sign:\n\n$$\\tan 120 = -\\sqrt{3}$$\n\n**Answer:** $-\\sqrt{3}$',0,'expression',NULL,5,233,'','',0),(299,'(a)','Solve $\\frac{1}{x+1} + \\frac{1}{x-1} = 0$ for $x$.','0','Single value (e.g., 7 or -5)','**Step 1:** Find a common denominator\n\nThe common denominator is $(x+1)(x-1)$.\n\n$$\\frac{1}{x+1} + \\frac{1}{x-1} = 0$$\n\n$$\\frac{(x-1)}{(x+1)(x-1)} + \\frac{(x+1)}{(x+1)(x-1)} = 0$$\n\n**Step 2:** Combine the fractions\n\n$$\\frac{(x-1) + (x+1)}{(x+1)(x-1)} = 0$$\n\n$$\\frac{2x}{(x+1)(x-1)} = 0$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for $x$\n\nFor a fraction to equal zero, the numerator must be zero (and denominator non-zero).\n\n$$2x = 0$$\n\n$$x = 0$$\n\n**Step 4:** Check excluded values\n\nThe solution $x = 0$ doesn\'t make either denominator zero ($x \\neq -1, 1$).\n\n**Answer:** $x = 0$',0,'numeric',NULL,5,234,'','',0),(300,'(a)','Solve $\\frac{2}{3x-1} - \\frac{4}{5x+2} = 0$ for $x$.','4','Single value (e.g., 3 or -8)','**Step 1:** Rearrange the equation\n\n$$\\frac{2}{3x-1} = \\frac{4}{5x+2}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Cross-multiply\n\n$$2(5x+2) = 4(3x-1)$$\n\n$$10x + 4 = 12x - 4$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for $x$\n\n$$10x - 12x = -4 - 4$$\n\n$$-2x = -8$$\n\n$$x = 4$$\n\n**Step 4:** Check excluded values\n\nThe solution $x = 4$ doesn\'t make either denominator zero ($x \\neq \\frac{1}{3}, -\\frac{2}{5}$).\n\n**Answer:** $x = 4$',0,'numeric',NULL,5,235,'','',0),(301,'(a)','Solve $\\frac{4x}{2x+1} - \\frac{x}{x-1} = 2$ for $x$.','1/2,-2','Two values separated by comma (e.g., 3,7 or -1/3,5)','**Step 1:** Find a common denominator\n\nThe common denominator is $(2x+1)(x-1)$.\n\n$$\\frac{4x(x-1)}{(2x+1)(x-1)} - \\frac{x(2x+1)}{(2x+1)(x-1)} = 2$$\n\n**Step 2:** Combine fractions\n\n$$\\frac{4x(x-1) - x(2x+1)}{(2x+1)(x-1)} = 2$$\n\n$$\\frac{4x^2 - 4x - 2x^2 - x}{(2x+1)(x-1)} = 2$$\n\n$$\\frac{2x^2 - 5x}{(2x+1)(x-1)} = 2$$\n\n**Step 3:** Clear the denominator\n\n$$2x^2 - 5x = 2(2x+1)(x-1)$$\n\n$$2x^2 - 5x = 2(2x^2 - x - 1)$$\n\n$$2x^2 - 5x = 4x^2 - 2x - 2$$\n\n**Step 4:** Rearrange to standard form\n\n$$0 = 4x^2 - 2x^2 - 2x + 5x - 2$$\n\n$$0 = 2x^2 + 3x - 2$$\n\n**Step 5:** Factor\n\n$$2x^2 + 3x - 2 = 0$$\n\n$$(2x - 1)(x + 2) = 0$$\n\n$$x = \\frac{1}{2} \\text{ or } x = -2$$\n\n**Step 6:** Check excluded values\n\nBoth solutions don\'t make denominators zero ($x \\neq -\\frac{1}{2}, 1$).\n\n**Answer:** $x = \\frac{1}{2}$ or $x = -2$',0,'expression',NULL,7,236,'','',0),(302,'(a)','Solve for $x$:\n\n$$10x^2 + 6x - 52 = 0$$','2,-13/5','Two values separated by comma (e.g., 5,-3/2 or 1,7)','**Step 1:** Identify coefficients\n\nGiven the quadratic equation $10x^2 + 6x - 52 = 0$.\n\nWhere $a = 10$, $b = 6$, $c = -52$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the quadratic formula\n\n$$x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$$\n\n**Step 3:** Substitute values\n\n$$x = \\frac{-6 \\pm \\sqrt{6^2 - 4(10)(-52)}}{2(10)}$$\n\n**Step 4:** Simplify\n\n$$x = \\frac{-6 \\pm \\sqrt{36 + 2080}}{20} = \\frac{-6 \\pm \\sqrt{2116}}{20}$$\n\nSince $\\sqrt{2116} = 46$,\n\n$$x = \\frac{-6 + 46}{20} \\text{ or } x = \\frac{-6 - 46}{20}$$\n\n**Step 5:** Calculate final answers\n\n$$x = \\frac{40}{20} = 2 \\text{ or } x = \\frac{-52}{20} = -\\frac{13}{5}$$\n\n**Answer:** $x = 2$ or $x = -\\frac{13}{5}$',0,'expression',NULL,5,237,'','',0),(303,'(a)','Solve $\\sqrt{x-1} = 1$.','2','Single value (e.g., 5 or 10)','**Step 1:** Square both sides\n\n$$\\sqrt{x-1} = 1$$\n\n$$(\\sqrt{x-1})^2 = 1^2$$\n\n$$x - 1 = 1$$\n\n**Step 2:** Solve for $x$\n\n$$x = 2$$\n\n**Step 3:** Check the solution\n\nSubstitute $x = 2$ into the original equation:\n\n$$\\sqrt{2-1} = \\sqrt{1} = 1$$ \n\n**Answer:** $x = 2$',0,'numeric',NULL,5,238,'','',0),(304,'(a)','Solve $\\sqrt{3x-2} - 3 = 1$.','6','Single value (e.g., 8 or 12)','**Step 1:** Isolate the square root\n\n$$\\sqrt{3x-2} - 3 = 1$$\n\n$$\\sqrt{3x-2} = 4$$\n\n**Step 2:** Square both sides\n\n$$(\\sqrt{3x-2})^2 = 4^2$$\n\n$$3x - 2 = 16$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for $x$\n\n$$3x = 18$$\n\n$$x = 6$$\n\n**Step 4:** Check the solution\n\nSubstitute $x = 6$ into the original equation:\n\n$$\\sqrt{3(6)-2} - 3 = \\sqrt{16} - 3 = 4 - 3 = 1$$ \n\n**Answer:** $x = 6$',0,'numeric',NULL,5,239,'','',0),(305,'(a)','Solve $\\sqrt{7-2x} + 2 = x$.','3','Single value (e.g., 5 or 9)','**Step 1:** Isolate the square root\n\n$$\\sqrt{7-2x} + 2 = x$$\n\n$$\\sqrt{7-2x} = x - 2$$\n\n**Step 2:** Square both sides\n\n$$(\\sqrt{7-2x})^2 = (x-2)^2$$\n\n$$7 - 2x = x^2 - 4x + 4$$\n\n**Step 3:** Rearrange to standard form\n\n$$0 = x^2 - 4x + 2x + 4 - 7$$\n\n$$0 = x^2 - 2x - 3$$\n\n**Step 4:** Factor and solve\n\n$$0 = (x-3)(x+1)$$\n\n$$x = 3 \\text{ or } x = -1$$\n\n**Step 5:** Check both solutions\n\nFor $x = 3$: $\\sqrt{7-6} + 2 = \\sqrt{1} + 2 = 1 + 2 = 3$ \n\nFor $x = -1$: $\\sqrt{7+2} + 2 = \\sqrt{9} + 2 = 3 + 2 = 5 \\neq -1$ \n\nThe solution $x = -1$ is extraneous.\n\n**Answer:** $x = 3$',0,'numeric',NULL,7,240,'','',0),(306,'(a)','Solve $|x-2| = 2$.','0,4','Two values separated by comma (e.g., 2,6 or -3,5)','**Step 1:** Set up two cases\n\n$$|x-2| = 2$$\n\n**Case 1:** $x - 2 = 2$\n\n**Case 2:** $x - 2 = -2$\n\n**Step 2:** Solve Case 1\n\n$$x - 2 = 2$$\n\n$$x = 4$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve Case 2\n\n$$x - 2 = -2$$\n\n$$x = 0$$\n\n**Step 4:** Verify both solutions\n\nFor $x = 4$: $|4-2| = |2| = 2$ \n\nFor $x = 0$: $|0-2| = |-2| = 2$ \n\n**Answer:** $x = 0$ or $x = 4$',0,'expression',NULL,5,241,'','',0),(307,'(a)','Solve $|2x-3| = 1$.','1,2','Two values separated by comma (e.g., 3,5 or -2,4)','**Step 1:** Set up two cases\n\n$$|2x-3| = 1$$\n\n**Case 1:** $2x - 3 = 1$\n\n**Case 2:** $2x - 3 = -1$\n\n**Step 2:** Solve Case 1\n\n$$2x - 3 = 1$$\n\n$$2x = 4$$\n\n$$x = 2$$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve Case 2\n\n$$2x - 3 = -1$$\n\n$$2x = 2$$\n\n$$x = 1$$\n\n**Step 4:** Verify both solutions\n\nFor $x = 2$: $|2(2)-3| = |1| = 1$ \n\nFor $x = 1$: $|2(1)-3| = |-1| = 1$ \n\n**Answer:** $x = 1$ or $x = 2$',0,'expression',NULL,5,242,'','',0),(308,'(a)','Solve $|2x| = x^2 + 1$.','-1,1','Two values separated by comma (e.g., -2,2 or -5,5)','**Step 1:** Set up two cases based on the sign of $x$\n\n$$|2x| = x^2 + 1$$\n\n**Case 1:** When $x \\geq 0$, then $|2x| = 2x$\n\n**Case 2:** When $x < 0$, then $|2x| = -2x$\n\n**Step 2:** Solve Case 1 ($x \\geq 0$)\n\n$$2x = x^2 + 1$$\n\n$$0 = x^2 - 2x + 1$$\n\n$$0 = (x-1)^2$$\n\n$$x = 1$$\n\nSince $1 \\geq 0$, this solution is valid.\n\n**Step 3:** Solve Case 2 ($x < 0$)\n\n$$-2x = x^2 + 1$$\n\n$$0 = x^2 + 2x + 1$$\n\n$$0 = (x+1)^2$$\n\n$$x = -1$$\n\nSince $-1 < 0$, this solution is valid.\n\n**Step 4:** Verify both solutions\n\nFor $x = 1$: $|2(1)| = 2$ and $1^2 + 1 = 2$ \n\nFor $x = -1$: $|2(-1)| = 2$ and $(-1)^2 + 1 = 2$ \n\n**Answer:** $x = -1$ or $x = 1$',0,'expression',NULL,7,243,'','',0),(309,'(a)','Rearrange $V = \\frac{4}{3}\\pi r^3$ to make $r$ the subject of the equation.','(3V/(4*pi))^(1/3)','Expression with cube root (e.g., $\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{5A}{2\\pi}}$ or $\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{7B}{3C}}$)','**Step 1:** Start with the formula\n\n$$V = \\frac{4}{3}\\pi r^3$$\n\n**Step 2:** Multiply both sides by $\\frac{3}{4\\pi}$\n\n$$\\frac{3V}{4\\pi} = r^3$$\n\n**Step 3:** Take the cube root of both sides\n\n$$r = \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{3V}{4\\pi}}$$\n\n**Answer:** $r = \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{3V}{4\\pi}}$',0,'expression',NULL,5,244,'','',0),(310,'(a)','Rearrange $qvB = \\frac{mv^2}{r}$ to make $v$ the subject.','(q*B*r)/m','Fraction expression (e.g., $\\frac{aCd}{m}$ or $\\frac{pQs}{n}$)','**Step 1:** Start with the formula\n\n$$qvB = \\frac{mv^2}{r}$$\n\n**Step 2:** Multiply both sides by $r$\n\n$$qvBr = mv^2$$\n\n**Step 3:** Divide both sides by $mv$\n\n$$\\frac{qBr}{m} = v$$\n\n**Answer:** $v = \\frac{qBr}{m}$',0,'expression',NULL,5,245,'','',0),(311,'(a)','Rearrange $E = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + \\frac{\\omega}{2} + U$ to make $v$ the subject of the equation.','sqrt((2*E-omega-2*U)/m)','Expression with square root (e.g., $\\sqrt{\\frac{3F-\\alpha-5V}{n}}$)','**Step 1:** Start with the formula\n\n$$E = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 + \\frac{\\omega}{2} + U$$\n\n**Step 2:** Subtract $\\frac{\\omega}{2} + U$ from both sides\n\n$$E - \\frac{\\omega}{2} - U = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2$$\n\n**Step 3:** Multiply both sides by 2\n\n$$2\\left(E - \\frac{\\omega}{2} - U\\right) = mv^2$$\n\n**Step 4:** Divide both sides by $m$\n\n$$\\frac{2\\left(E - \\frac{\\omega}{2} - U\\right)}{m} = v^2$$\n\n**Step 5:** Take the square root of both sides\n\n$$v = \\sqrt{\\frac{2\\left(E - \\frac{\\omega}{2} - U\\right)}{m}}$$\n\nOr equivalently:\n\n$$v = \\sqrt{\\frac{2E - \\omega - 2U}{m}}$$\n\n**Answer:** $v = \\sqrt{\\frac{2E - \\omega - 2U}{m}}$',0,'expression',NULL,7,246,'','',0),(312,'(a)','Given that $ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 2x^3 + x^2 - 2x$, find the values of $a$, $b$, $c$ and $d$.','a=2,b=1,c=-2,d=0','Four values (e.g., a=5,b=3,c=-4,d=1)','**Step 1:** Write out the equation\n\n$$ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 2x^3 + x^2 - 2x$$\n\n**Step 2:** Compare coefficients of like terms\n\nCoefficient of $x^3$: $a = 2$\n\nCoefficient of $x^2$: $b = 1$\n\nCoefficient of $x^1$: $c = -2$\n\nConstant term: $d = 0$\n\n**Answer:** $a = 2$, $b = 1$, $c = -2$, $d = 0$',0,'manual',NULL,5,247,'','',0),(313,'(a)','The following equation is true for all values of $x$:\n\n$$ax^2 + b(x+2) + 2c = 3x^2 + 3x + 4$$\n\nFind the values of $a$, $b$ and $c$.','a=3,b=3,c=-1','Three values (e.g., a=7,b=5,c=-2)','**Step 1:** Expand the left side\n\n$$ax^2 + b(x+2) + 2c = 3x^2 + 3x + 4$$\n\n$$ax^2 + bx + 2b + 2c = 3x^2 + 3x + 4$$\n\n**Step 2:** Compare coefficients of like terms\n\nCoefficient of $x^2$: $a = 3$\n\nCoefficient of $x^1$: $b = 3$\n\nConstant term: $2b + 2c = 4$\n\n**Step 3:** Solve for $c$\n\n$$2b + 2c = 4$$\n\n$$2(3) + 2c = 4$$\n\n$$6 + 2c = 4$$\n\n$$2c = -2$$\n\n$$c = -1$$\n\n**Answer:** $a = 3$, $b = 3$, $c = -1$',0,'manual',NULL,5,248,'','',0),(314,'(a)','The following equation is true for all $x$: $(x+a)(2x+b) = 2x^2 + x - 1$.\n\nFind the values of $a$ and $b$.','a=1,b=-1 or a=-1/2,b=2','Two sets of values (e.g., a=3,b=-2 or a=-1/3,b=5)','**Step 1:** Expand the left side\n\n$$(x+a)(2x+b) = 2x^2 + x - 1$$\n\n$$2x^2 + bx + 2ax + ab = 2x^2 + x - 1$$\n\n$$2x^2 + (b+2a)x + ab = 2x^2 + x - 1$$\n\n**Step 2:** Compare coefficients\n\nCoefficient of $x^2$: $2 = 2$ \n\nCoefficient of $x^1$: $b + 2a = 1$ ... (1)\n\nConstant term: $ab = -1$ ... (2)\n\n**Step 3:** Solve the system\n\nFrom equation (2): $b = -\\frac{1}{a}$\n\nSubstitute into equation (1):\n\n$$-\\frac{1}{a} + 2a = 1$$\n\nMultiply by $a$:\n\n$$-1 + 2a^2 = a$$\n\n$$2a^2 - a - 1 = 0$$\n\n$$(2a + 1)(a - 1) = 0$$\n\n$$a = 1 \\text{ or } a = -\\frac{1}{2}$$\n\n**Step 4:** Find corresponding values of $b$\n\nIf $a = 1$: $b = -\\frac{1}{1} = -1$\n\nIf $a = -\\frac{1}{2}$: $b = -\\frac{1}{-\\frac{1}{2}} = 2$\n\n**Answer:** $a = 1, b = -1$ or $a = -\\frac{1}{2}, b = 2$',0,'manual',NULL,7,249,'','',0),(315,'(a)','Factorise $12 - xy + 3y - 4x$.','(3-x)(4+y)','Factored form (e.g., $(2-a)(5+b)$ or $(p+q)(r-s)$)','**Step 1:** Rearrange the terms\n\n$$12 - xy + 3y - 4x$$\n\n$$= 12 - 4x + 3y - xy$$\n\n**Step 2:** Group into pairs\n\n$$= (12 - 4x) + (3y - xy)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Factor each group\n\n$$= 4(3 - x) + y(3 - x)$$\n\n**Step 4:** Factor out the common binomial $(3 - x)$\n\n$$= (3 - x)(4 + y)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(3 - x)(4 + y)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,250,'','',0),(316,'(a)','Factorise $y^2t + 3\\cos(x) - y^2\\cos(x) - 3t$.','(t-cos(x))(y^2-3)','Factored form (e.g., $(s-\\sin(x))(z^2-5)$ or $(a-b)(c+d)$)','**Step 1:** Rearrange the terms\n\n$$y^2t + 3\\cos(x) - y^2\\cos(x) - 3t$$\n\n$$= y^2t - y^2\\cos(x) + 3\\cos(x) - 3t$$\n\n**Step 2:** Group into pairs\n\n$$= (y^2t - y^2\\cos(x)) + (3\\cos(x) - 3t)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Factor each group\n\n$$= y^2(t - \\cos(x)) + 3(\\cos(x) - t)$$\n\n**Step 4:** Adjust signs\n\nNote that $(\\cos(x) - t) = -(t - \\cos(x))$:\n\n$$= y^2(t - \\cos(x)) - 3(t - \\cos(x))$$\n\n**Step 5:** Factor out the common binomial $(t - \\cos(x))$\n\n$$= (t - \\cos(x))(y^2 - 3)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(t - \\cos(x))(y^2 - 3)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,251,'','',0),(317,'(a)','Factorise $x^2 + x(5 - y) - 5y$.','(x+5)(x-y)','Factored form (e.g., $(x+7)(x-z)$ or $(a+b)(c-d)$)','**Step 1:** Expand the brackets\n\n$$x^2 + x(5 - y) - 5y$$\n\n$$= x^2 + 5x - xy - 5y$$\n\n**Step 2:** Group into pairs\n\n$$= (x^2 + 5x) + (-xy - 5y)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Factor each group\n\n$$= x(x + 5) - y(x + 5)$$\n\n**Step 4:** Factor out the common binomial $(x + 5)$\n\n$$= (x + 5)(x - y)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x + 5)(x - y)$',0,'expression',NULL,7,252,'','',0),(318,'(a)','Factorise $x^2 - 7x - 8$.','(x-8)(x+1)','Factored form (e.g., $(x-5)(x+3)$ or $(x+a)(x+b)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the values\n\n$$x^2 - 7x - 8$$\n\nWe need two numbers that multiply to $-8$ and add to $-7$.\n\n**Step 2:** Find the two numbers\n\nThe numbers are $-8$ and $1$:\n- $(-8) \\times 1 = -8$ \n- $(-8) + 1 = -7$ \n\n**Step 3:** Write the factorisation\n\n$$x^2 - 7x - 8 = (x - 8)(x + 1)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x - 8)(x + 1)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,253,'','',0),(319,'(a)','Factorise $2x^2 + 3x - 2$.','(x+2)(2x-1)','Factored form (e.g., $(x+5)(3x-2)$ or $(x+a)(bx+c)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the values\n\n$$2x^2 + 3x - 2$$\n\nWe need two numbers that multiply to $2 \\times (-2) = -4$ and add to $3$.\n\n**Step 2:** Find the two numbers\n\nThe numbers are $4$ and $-1$:\n- $4 \\times (-1) = -4$ \n- $4 + (-1) = 3$ \n\n**Step 3:** Split the middle term\n\n$$2x^2 + 3x - 2 = 2x^2 + 4x - x - 2$$\n\n**Step 4:** Group and factor\n\n$$= (2x^2 + 4x) + (-x - 2)$$\n\n$$= 2x(x + 2) - 1(x + 2)$$\n\n$$= (x + 2)(2x - 1)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x + 2)(2x - 1)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,254,'','',0),(320,'(a)','Factorise $3x^2 + 14x - 5$.','(x+5)(3x-1)','Factored form (e.g., $(x+2)(5x-3)$ or $(x+a)(bx+c)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the values\n\n$$3x^2 + 14x - 5$$\n\nWe need two numbers that multiply to $3 \\times (-5) = -15$ and add to $14$.\n\n**Step 2:** Find the two numbers\n\nThe numbers are $15$ and $-1$:\n- $15 \\times (-1) = -15$ \n- $15 + (-1) = 14$ \n\n**Step 3:** Split the middle term\n\n$$3x^2 + 14x - 5 = 3x^2 + 15x - x - 5$$\n\n**Step 4:** Group and factor\n\n$$= (3x^2 + 15x) + (-x - 5)$$\n\n$$= 3x(x + 5) - 1(x + 5)$$\n\n$$= (x + 5)(3x - 1)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x + 5)(3x - 1)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,255,'','',0),(321,'(a)','Factorise $x^3 - 64$.','(x-4)(x^2+4x+16)','Factored form (e.g., $(y-5)(y^2+5y+25)$ or $(a-b)(a^2+ab+b^2)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the cubes\n\n$$x^3 - 64 = x^3 - 4^3$$\n\nHere, $a = x$ and $b = 4$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the difference of two cubes formula\n\n$$a^3 - b^3 = (a-b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values\n\n$$(x-4)(x^2 + x(4) + 4^2)$$\n\n$$(x-4)(x^2 + 4x + 16)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x-4)(x^2 + 4x + 16)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,256,'','',0),(322,'(a)','Factorise $27t^3 - x^3$.','(3t-x)(9t^2+3tx+x^2)','Factored form (e.g., $(2p-q)(4p^2+2pq+q^2)$ or $(a-b)(a^2+ab+b^2)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the cubes\n\n$$27t^3 - x^3 = (3t)^3 - x^3$$\n\nHere, $a = 3t$ and $b = x$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the difference of two cubes formula\n\n$$a^3 - b^3 = (a-b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values\n\n$$(3t-x)((3t)^2 + (3t)(x) + x^2)$$\n\n$$(3t-x)(9t^2 + 3tx + x^2)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(3t-x)(9t^2 + 3tx + x^2)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,257,'','',0),(323,'(a)','Using the Difference of Two Cubes formula, factorise $x^3 - 1$.','(x-1)(x^2+x+1)','Factored form (e.g., $(y-1)(y^2+y+1)$ or $(a-1)(a^2+a+1)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the cubes\n\n$$x^3 - 1 = x^3 - 1^3$$\n\nHere, $a = x$ and $b = 1$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the difference of two cubes formula\n\n$$a^3 - b^3 = (a-b)(a^2 + ab + b^2)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values\n\n$$(x-1)(x^2 + x(1) + 1^2)$$\n\n$$(x-1)(x^2 + x + 1)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x-1)(x^2 + x + 1)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,258,'','',0),(324,'(a)','Factorise $x^3 + 27$.','(x+3)(x^2-3x+9)','Factored form (e.g., $(y+2)(y^2-2y+4)$ or $(a+b)(a^2-ab+b^2)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the cubes\n\n$$x^3 + 27 = x^3 + 3^3$$\n\nHere, $a = x$ and $b = 3$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the sum of two cubes formula\n\n$$a^3 + b^3 = (a+b)(a^2 - ab + b^2)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values\n\n$$(x+3)(x^2 - x(3) + 3^2)$$\n\n$$(x+3)(x^2 - 3x + 9)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(x+3)(x^2 - 3x + 9)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,259,'','',0),(325,'(a)','Factorise $64y^3 + 1$.','(4y+1)(16y^2-4y+1)','Factored form (e.g., $(3z+1)(9z^2-3z+1)$ or $(a+b)(a^2-ab+b^2)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the cubes\n\n$$64y^3 + 1 = (4y)^3 + 1^3$$\n\nHere, $a = 4y$ and $b = 1$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the sum of two cubes formula\n\n$$a^3 + b^3 = (a+b)(a^2 - ab + b^2)$$\n\n**Step 3:** Substitute the values\n\n$$(4y+1)((4y)^2 - (4y)(1) + 1^2)$$\n\n$$(4y+1)(16y^2 - 4y + 1)$$\n\n**Answer:** $(4y+1)(16y^2 - 4y + 1)$',0,'expression',NULL,5,260,'','',0),(326,'(a)','Factorise $y^3 + x^3$ using the sum of two cubes method.','(y+x)(y^2-xy+x^2)','Factored form (e.g., $(a+b)(a^2-ab+b^2)$ or $(p+q)(p^2-pq+q^2)$)','**Step 1:** Identify the cubes\n\n$$y^3 + x^3$$\n\nHere, $a = y$ and $b = x$.\n\n**Step 2:** Apply the sum of two cubes formula\n\n$$a