\pm 1.96$\n\n**Step 5: Make a decision**\n\nSince $|z| = 2.385 > 1.96$, we reject the null hypothesis.\n\n**Step 6: Conclusion**\n\nWe reject $H_0$ at the 5% significance level. There is sufficient evidence to conclude that the average commute time has changed from 42 minutes.\n\n**Answer:**\n- Null Hypothesis: $H_0: \\mu = 42$\n- Alternative Hypothesis: $H_1: \\mu \\neq 42$\n- Test Statistic: $z = -2.385$\n- Conclusion: Reject $H_0$\n- Reason: $|z| = 2.385 > 1.96$, so we reject the null hypothesis at the 5% level of significance.',0,'manual',NULL,10,456,'','solutions/hypothesis_commute_time.png',0),(625,'(a)','A technology company claims that **65%** of adults own a smartphone.\n\nA consumer research group believes this proportion has changed and surveys a random sample of **600 adults**. They find that **416 adults** own a smartphone.\n\nCarry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if there is evidence that the proportion of adults who own smartphones has changed from 65%.\n\nState your **null hypothesis** and **alternative hypothesis**, show your **calculations**, state your **conclusion**, and give a **reason** for your conclusion.\n\n**Format your answer as:**\n\\`\\`\\`\nNull Hypothesis: [H]\nAlternative Hypothesis: [H]\nSample Proportion: p = [value]\nTest Statistic: z = [calculated value]\nConclusion: [Reject H / Fail to reject H]\nReason: [explanation based on z-value and critical value]\n\\`\\`\\`','Null Hypothesis: H: p = 0.65\nAlternative Hypothesis: H: p  0.65\nSample Proportion: p = 0.693\nTest Statistic: z = 2.225\nConclusion: Reject H\nReason: |z| = 2.225 > 1.96, so we reject the null hypothesis. There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that the proportion of adults who own smartphones has changed from 65%.','Multiple components including hypotheses, sample proportion, test statistic, conclusion, and reason','**Step 1: State the hypotheses**\n\n$H_0: p = 0.65$ (null hypothesis - the population proportion who own smartphones is 65%)\n\n$H_1: p \\neq 0.65$ (alternative hypothesis - the proportion has changed)\n\n**Step 2: Identify the given information**\n\n- Claimed proportion: $p = 0.65$\n- Sample size: $n = 600$ adults\n- Number with smartphones: $x = 416$\n- Sample proportion: $\\hat{p} = \\frac{416}{600} = 0.693$\n- Significance level: $\\alpha = 0.05$ (5%)\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the test statistic**\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.693 - 0.65}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.65(1-0.65)}{600}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.043}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.65 \\times 0.35}{600}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.043}{\\sqrt{0.00038}} = \\frac{0.043}{0.01947} = 2.225$$\n\n**Step 4: Determine the critical value**\n\nFor a two-tailed test at $\\alpha = 0.05$:\n- Critical z-values: $\\pm 1.96$\n\n**Step 5: Make a decision**\n\nSince $|z| = 2.225 > 1.96$, we reject the null hypothesis.\n\n**Step 6: Conclusion**\n\nWe reject $H_0$ at the 5% significance level. There is sufficient evidence to conclude that the proportion of adults who own smartphones has changed from 65%.\n\n**Answer:**\n- Null Hypothesis: $H_0: p = 0.65$\n- Alternative Hypothesis: $H_1: p \\neq 0.65$\n- Sample Proportion: $\\hat{p} = 0.693$\n- Test Statistic: $z = 2.225$\n- Conclusion: Reject $H_0$\n- Reason: $|z| = 2.225 > 1.96$, so we reject the null hypothesis at the 5% level of significance.',0,'manual',NULL,10,457,'','solutions/hypothesis_test_proportion_q457.png',0),(626,'(a)','In the previous election, **48%** of voters in a constituency supported Party A.\n\nA political analyst wants to test if support for Party A has changed. A poll of **800 randomly selected voters** finds that **352 voters** support Party A.\n\nCarry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if there is evidence that support for Party A has changed from 48%.\n\nState your **null hypothesis** and **alternative hypothesis**, show your **calculations**, state your **conclusion**, and give a **reason** for your conclusion.\n\n**Format your answer as:**\n\\`\\`\\`\nNull Hypothesis: [H]\nAlternative Hypothesis: [H]\nSample Proportion: p = [value]\nTest Statistic: z = [calculated value]\nConclusion: [Reject H / Fail to reject H]\nReason: [explanation based on z-value and critical value]\n\\`\\`\\`','Null Hypothesis: H: p = 0.48\nAlternative Hypothesis: H: p  0.48\nSample Proportion: p = 0.44\nTest Statistic: z = -2.265\nConclusion: Reject H\nReason: |z| = 2.265 > 1.96, so we reject the null hypothesis. There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that support for Party A has changed from 48%.','Multiple components including hypotheses, sample proportion, test statistic, conclusion, and reason','**Step 1: State the hypotheses**\n\n$H_0: p = 0.48$ (null hypothesis - the population proportion supporting Party A is 48%)\n\n$H_1: p \\neq 0.48$ (alternative hypothesis - the proportion has changed)\n\n**Step 2: Identify the given information**\n\n- Previous proportion: $p = 0.48$\n- Sample size: $n = 800$ voters\n- Number supporting Party A: $x = 352$\n- Sample proportion: $\\hat{p} = \\frac{352}{800} = 0.44$\n- Significance level: $\\alpha = 0.05$ (5%)\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the test statistic**\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.44 - 0.48}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.48(1-0.48)}{800}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{-0.04}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.48 \\times 0.52}{800}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{-0.04}{\\sqrt{0.0003120}} = \\frac{-0.04}{0.01766} = -2.265$$\n\n**Step 4: Determine the critical value**\n\nFor a two-tailed test at $\\alpha = 0.05$:\n- Critical z-values: $\\pm 1.96$\n\n**Step 5: Make a decision**\n\nSince $|z| = 2.265 > 1.96$, we reject the null hypothesis.\n\n**Step 6: Conclusion**\n\nWe reject $H_0$ at the 5% significance level. There is sufficient evidence to conclude that support for Party A has changed from 48%.\n\n**Answer:**\n- Null Hypothesis: $H_0: p = 0.48$\n- Alternative Hypothesis: $H_1: p \\neq 0.48$\n- Sample Proportion: $\\hat{p} = 0.44$\n- Test Statistic: $z = -2.265$\n- Conclusion: Reject $H_0$\n- Reason: $|z| = 2.265 > 1.96$, so we reject the null hypothesis at the 5% level of significance.',0,'manual',NULL,10,458,'','solutions/hypothesis_test_proportion_q458.png',0),(627,'(a)','A manufacturing company claims that **3%** of their products are defective.\n\nA quality inspector suspects this rate has changed and examines a random sample of **500 products**. They find **21 defective products**.\n\nCarry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if there is evidence that the defect rate is different from 3%.\n\nState your **null hypothesis** and **alternative hypothesis**, show your **calculations**, state your **conclusion**, and give a **reason** for your conclusion.\n\n**Format your answer as:**\n\\`\\`\\`\nNull Hypothesis: [H]\nAlternative Hypothesis: [H]\nSample Proportion: p = [value]\nTest Statistic: z = [calculated value]\nConclusion: [Reject H / Fail to reject H]\nReason: [explanation based on z-value and critical value]\n\\`\\`\\`','Null Hypothesis: H: p = 0.03\nAlternative Hypothesis: H: p  0.03\nSample Proportion: p = 0.042\nTest Statistic: z = 1.573\nConclusion: Fail to reject H\nReason: |z| = 1.573 < 1.96, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is insufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that the defect rate is different from 3%.','Multiple components including hypotheses, sample proportion, test statistic, conclusion, and reason','**Step 1: State the hypotheses**\n\n$H_0: p = 0.03$ (null hypothesis - the population proportion of defective products is 3%)\n\n$H_1: p \\neq 0.03$ (alternative hypothesis - the proportion is different from 3%)\n\n**Note:** This is a **two-tailed test** because we\'re testing if the rate is **different** (could be higher or lower).\n\n**Step 2: Identify the given information**\n\n- Claimed proportion: $p = 0.03$\n- Sample size: $n = 500$ products\n- Number of defective products: $x = 21$\n- Sample proportion: $\\hat{p} = \\frac{21}{500} = 0.042$\n- Significance level: $\\alpha = 0.05$ (5%)\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the test statistic**\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.042 - 0.03}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.03(1-0.03)}{500}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.012}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.03 \\times 0.97}{500}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.012}{\\sqrt{0.0000582}} = \\frac{0.012}{0.007628} = 1.573$$\n\n**Step 4: Determine the critical value**\n\nFor a **two-tailed test** at $\\alpha = 0.05$:\n- Critical z-values: $\\pm 1.96$\n\n**Step 5: Make a decision**\n\nSince $|z| = 1.573 < 1.96$, we **fail to reject** the null hypothesis.\n\n**Step 6: Conclusion**\n\nWe fail to reject $H_0$ at the 5% significance level. There is **insufficient evidence** to conclude that the defect rate is different from 3%. The observed defect rate of 4.2% could reasonably have occurred by chance if the true rate is 3%.\n\n**Answer:**\n- Null Hypothesis: $H_0: p = 0.03$\n- Alternative Hypothesis: $H_1: p \\neq 0.03$\n- Sample Proportion: $\\hat{p} = 0.042$\n- Test Statistic: $z = 1.573$\n- Conclusion: Fail to reject $H_0$\n- Reason: $|z| = 1.573 < 1.96$, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis at the 5% level of significance.',0,'manual',NULL,10,459,'','solutions/hypothesis_test_proportion_q459_wzYxfzN.png',0),(628,'(a)','A laptop manufacturer claims that their batteries last an average of **8 hours** on a single charge, with a standard deviation of **1.2 hours**.\n\nA technology reviewer believes the mean battery life may have changed and tests a random sample of **40 laptops**. The sample has a mean battery life of **7.65 hours**.\n\nUsing the **p-value method**, carry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if there is evidence that the mean battery life is different from 8 hours.\n\n**(i)** State $H_0$ and $H_1$.\n\n**(ii)** Calculate the value of the test statistic.\n\n**(iii)** Calculate the p-value for the test statistic.\n\n**(iv)** Use the p-value to state if the result is significant at the 5% level of significance. Explain your conclusion.','(i) H:  = 8, H:   8\n(ii) z = -1.845\n(iii) p-value = 0.0650\n(iv) Since p-value = 0.0650 > 0.05, the result is not significant. We fail to reject H. There is insufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that the mean battery life is different from 8 hours.','Multiple components including hypotheses, test statistic, p-value, and conclusion','**(i) State the hypotheses**\n\n$H_0: \\mu = 8$ (null hypothesis - the population mean battery life is 8 hours)\n\n$H_1: \\mu \\neq 8$ (alternative hypothesis - the mean has changed)\n\n**(ii) Calculate the test statistic**\n\n**Given:**\n- Claimed mean: $\\mu_0 = 8$ hours\n- Sample size: $n = 40$ laptops\n- Sample mean: $\\bar{x} = 7.65$ hours\n- Standard deviation: $\\sigma = 1.2$ hours\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu_0}{\\sigma/\\sqrt{n}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{7.65 - 8}{1.2/\\sqrt{40}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{-0.35}{1.2/6.325} = \\frac{-0.35}{0.1897} = -1.845$$\n\n**(iii) Calculate the p-value**\n\nFor a **two-tailed test**, the p-value is the sum of the probabilities in both tails:\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = P(Z \\leq -1.845) + P(Z \\geq 1.845)$$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times P(Z \\geq 1.845)$$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times [1 - P(Z \\leq 1.845)]$$\n\nUsing the standard normal table: $P(Z \\leq 1.845) \\approx 0.9675$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times [1 - 0.9675] = 2 \\times 0.0325 = 0.0650$$\n\n**(iv) Decision using p-value**\n\n**Decision Rule:** If p-value  , reject $H_0$; if p-value > , fail to reject $H_0$.\n\nSince $p\\text{-value} = 0.0650 > 0.05$ (), we **fail to reject** $H_0$.\n\n**Conclusion:** There is insufficient evidence at the 5% level of significance to conclude that the mean battery life is different from 8 hours.\n\n**Interpretation:** The p-value of 0.0650 means there is a 6.50% chance of observing a sample mean as extreme as 7.65 hours (or more extreme) if the true mean is actually 8 hours. This is greater than our significance level of 5%, so the result is not statistically significant.',0,'manual',NULL,10,460,'','solutions/pvalue_test_q460.png',0),(629,'(a)','A delivery company claims that packages are delivered in an average of **3.5 days**, with a standard deviation of **0.8 days**.\n\nA customer service manager believes the mean delivery time may have changed and examines a random sample of **50 deliveries**. The sample has a mean delivery time of **3.75 days**.\n\nUsing the **p-value method**, carry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if there is evidence that the mean delivery time is different from 3.5 days.\n\n**(i)** State $H_0$ and $H_1$.\n\n**(ii)** Calculate the value of the test statistic.\n\n**(iii)** Calculate the p-value for the test statistic.\n\n**(iv)** Use the p-value to state if the result is significant at the 5% level of significance. Explain your conclusion.','(i) H:  = 3.5, H:   3.5\n(ii) z = 2.210\n(iii) p-value = 0.0272\n(iv) Since p-value = 0.0272 < 0.05, the result is significant. We reject H. There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that the mean delivery time is different from 3.5 days.','Multiple components including hypotheses, test statistic, p-value, and conclusion','**(i) State the hypotheses**\n\n$H_0: \\mu = 3.5$ (null hypothesis - the population mean delivery time is 3.5 days)\n\n$H_1: \\mu \\neq 3.5$ (alternative hypothesis - the mean has changed)\n\n**(ii) Calculate the test statistic**\n\n**Given:**\n- Claimed mean: $\\mu_0 = 3.5$ days\n- Sample size: $n = 50$ deliveries\n- Sample mean: $\\bar{x} = 3.75$ days\n- Standard deviation: $\\sigma = 0.8$ days\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\bar{x} - \\mu_0}{\\sigma/\\sqrt{n}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{3.75 - 3.5}{0.8/\\sqrt{50}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.25}{0.8/7.071} = \\frac{0.25}{0.1131} = 2.210$$\n\n**(iii) Calculate the p-value**\n\nFor a **two-tailed test**, the p-value is the sum of the probabilities in both tails:\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = P(Z \\leq -2.210) + P(Z \\geq 2.210)$$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times P(Z \\geq 2.210)$$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times [1 - P(Z \\leq 2.210)]$$\n\nUsing the standard normal table: $P(Z \\leq 2.210) \\approx 0.9864$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times [1 - 0.9864] = 2 \\times 0.0136 = 0.0272$$\n\n**(iv) Decision using p-value**\n\n**Decision Rule:** If p-value  , reject $H_0$; if p-value > , fail to reject $H_0$.\n\nSince $p\\text{-value} = 0.0272 < 0.05$ (), we **reject** $H_0$.\n\n**Conclusion:** There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level of significance to conclude that the mean delivery time is different from 3.5 days.\n\n**Interpretation:** The p-value of 0.0272 means there is only a 2.72% chance of observing a sample mean as extreme as 3.75 days (or more extreme) if the true mean is actually 3.5 days. This is less than our significance level of 5%, so the result is statistically significant. This p-value represents the **lowest level of significance** at which we could reject $H_0$.',0,'manual',NULL,10,461,'','solutions/pvalue_test_q461.png',0),(630,'(a)','An online retailer claims that **75%** of their customers are satisfied with their service.\n\nA market research firm believes this proportion may have changed and surveys a random sample of **200 customers**. They find that **137 customers** are satisfied.\n\nUsing the **p-value method**, carry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if there is evidence that the proportion of satisfied customers is different from 75%.\n\n**(i)** State $H_0$ and $H_1$.\n\n**(ii)** Calculate the value of the test statistic.\n\n**(iii)** Calculate the p-value for the test statistic.\n\n**(iv)** Use the p-value to state if the result is significant at the 5% level of significance. Explain your conclusion.','(i) H: p = 0.75, H: p  0.75\n(ii) z = -2.123\n(iii) p-value = 0.0338\n(iv) Since p-value = 0.0338 < 0.05, the result is significant. We reject H. There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level to conclude that the proportion of satisfied customers is different from 75%.','Multiple components including hypotheses, test statistic, p-value, and conclusion','**(i) State the hypotheses**\n\n$H_0: p = 0.75$ (null hypothesis - the population proportion of satisfied customers is 75%)\n\n$H_1: p \\neq 0.75$ (alternative hypothesis - the proportion has changed)\n\n**(ii) Calculate the test statistic**\n\n**Given:**\n- Claimed proportion: $p = 0.75$\n- Sample size: $n = 200$ customers\n- Number satisfied: $x = 137$\n- Sample proportion: $\\hat{p} = \\frac{137}{200} = 0.685$\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{0.685 - 0.75}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.75(1-0.75)}{200}}}$$\n\n$$z = \\frac{-0.065}{\\sqrt{\\frac{0.75 \\times 0.25}{200}}} = \\frac{-0.065}{\\sqrt{0.0009375}} = \\frac{-0.065}{0.03062} = -2.123$$\n\n**(iii) Calculate the p-value**\n\nFor a **two-tailed test**, the p-value is the sum of the probabilities in both tails:\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = P(Z \\leq -2.123) + P(Z \\geq 2.123)$$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times P(Z \\geq 2.123)$$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times [1 - P(Z \\leq 2.123)]$$\n\nUsing the standard normal table: $P(Z \\leq 2.123) \\approx 0.9831$\n\n$$p\\text{-value} = 2 \\times [1 - 0.9831] = 2 \\times 0.0169 = 0.0338$$\n\n**(iv) Decision using p-value**\n\n**Decision Rule:** If p-value  , reject $H_0$; if p-value > , fail to reject $H_0$.\n\nSince $p\\text{-value} = 0.0338 < 0.05$ (), we **reject** $H_0$.\n\n**Conclusion:** There is sufficient evidence at the 5% level of significance to conclude that the proportion of satisfied customers is different from 75%.\n\n**Interpretation:** The p-value of 0.0338 (or 3.38%) represents the **lowest level of significance** at which we could reject $H_0$. There is only a 3.38% chance of observing a sample proportion as extreme as 68.5% (or more extreme) if the true proportion is actually 75%. Since this is less than our significance level of 5%, the result is statistically significant.',0,'manual',NULL,10,462,'','solutions/pvalue_test_q462.png',0),(631,'(a)','A market research company surveys a random sample of **400 teenagers** about their social media usage.\n\nThey find that **248 teenagers** use social media for more than 2 hours per day.\n\nConstruct a **95% confidence interval** for the proportion of all teenagers who use social media for more than 2 hours per day.','(0.572, 0.668)','Interval in format (lower, upper) to 3 decimal places (e.g., (0.572, 0.668))','**Step 1: Identify the given information**\n\n- Sample size: $n = 400$ teenagers\n- Number who use social media > 2 hours: $x = 248$\n- Sample proportion: $\\hat{p} = \\frac{248}{400} = 0.62$\n- Confidence level: 95%, so $z = 1.96$\n\n**Step 2: Calculate the standard error**\n\n$$SE = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}$$\n\n$$SE = \\sqrt{\\frac{0.62(1-0.62)}{400}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{0.62 \\times 0.38}{400}}$$\n\n$$SE = \\sqrt{\\frac{0.2356}{400}} = \\sqrt{0.000589} = 0.02427$$\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the margin of error**\n\n$$ME = z \\times SE = 1.96 \\times 0.02427 = 0.0476$$\n\n**Step 4: Calculate the confidence interval**\n\n$$\\text{Lower bound} = \\hat{p} - ME = 0.62 - 0.0476 = 0.5724 \\approx 0.572$$\n\n$$\\text{Upper bound} = \\hat{p} + ME = 0.62 + 0.0476 = 0.6676 \\approx 0.668$$\n\n**Answer:** The 95% confidence interval is **(0.572, 0.668)** or **(57.2%, 66.8%)**.\n\n**Interpretation:** We are 95% confident that the true proportion of all teenagers who use social media for more than 2 hours per day is between 57.2% and 66.8%.',0,'numeric',NULL,5,463,'','solutions/ci_proportion_q463.png',0),(632,'(a)','A quality control manager inspects a random sample of **500 products** from a production line.\n\nThey find that **20 products** are defective.\n\nConstruct a **95% confidence interval** for the proportion of all products from this production line that are defective.','(0.023, 0.057)','Interval in format (lower, upper) to 3 decimal places (e.g., (0.023, 0.057))','**Step 1: Identify the given information**\n\n- Sample size: $n = 500$ products\n- Number defective: $x = 20$\n- Sample proportion: $\\hat{p} = \\frac{20}{500} = 0.04$\n- Confidence level: 95%, so $z = 1.96$\n\n**Step 2: Calculate the standard error**\n\n$$SE = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{p}(1-\\hat{p})}{n}}$$\n\n$$SE = \\sqrt{\\frac{0.04(1-0.04)}{500}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{0.04 \\times 0.96}{500}}$$\n\n$$SE = \\sqrt{\\frac{0.0384}{500}} = \\sqrt{0.0000768} = 0.00876$$\n\n**Step 3: Calculate the margin of error**\n\n$$ME = z \\times SE = 1.96 \\times 0.00876 = 0.01717$$\n\n**Step 4: Calculate the confidence interval**\n\n$$\\text{Lower bound} = \\hat{p} - ME = 0.04 - 0.01717 = 0.02283 \\approx 0.023$$\n\n$$\\text{Upper bound} = \\hat{p} + ME = 0.04 + 0.01717 = 0.05717 \\approx 0.057$$\n\n**Answer:** The 95% confidence interval is **(0.023, 0.057)** or **(2.3%, 5.7%)**.\n\n**Interpretation:** We are 95% confident that the true proportion of defective products from this production line is between 2.3% and 5.7%.',0,'numeric',NULL,5,464,'','solutions/ci_proportion_q464.png',0);
