	ext{Mean} = rac{65 + 72 + 81 + 75 + 87}{5} = rac{380}{5} = 76\n$$\n\nThe student\'s average score is 76%.\n\n### Key Properties of the Mean\n\n1. **Sensitive to outliers**: Extreme values significantly affect the mean\n2. **Balance point**: The mean is the balance point of the data\n3. **Uses all data**: Every value in the dataset influences the mean\n4. **Most common measure**: Widely used in statistics and everyday life\n\n### When to Use the Mean\n\n **Use the mean when:**\n- Data is roughly symmetrical (no extreme outliers)\n- You want to use all values in your calculation\n- Comparing groups of similar size\n\n **Don\'t use the mean when:**\n- Data has extreme outliers (use median instead)\n- Data is highly skewed\n- You\'re working with categorical data\n\n### Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\n1. **Forgetting to count all values** when dividing\n2. **Confusing mean with median or mode**\n3. **Using mean with skewed data** where median would be better\n4. **Not checking for outliers** before calculating\n\n### Practice Tips\n- Always double-check your addition\n- Count your values carefully\n- Ask: \"Does this answer make sense?\"\n- The mean should fall between the smallest and largest values\n',0.582634687423706,'The Mean (Average)','notes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(17,'2025-10-31 21:31:24.137128','inferential-stats','what is the mean','## The Mean (Average)\n\nThe **mean** is a measure of central tendency that represents the typical or central value in a dataset. It is commonly called the **average**.\n\n### Definition\nThe mean is calculated by adding all values in a dataset and dividing by the number of values:\n\n$$\n	ext{Mean} = rac{	ext{Sum of all values}}{	ext{Number of values}} = rac{\\sum x}{n}\n$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\sum x$ = sum of all values\n- $n$ = number of values\n\n### Example 1: Simple Mean\nFind the mean of: 3, 7, 8, 10, 12\n\n**Solution:**\n$$\n	ext{Mean} = rac{3 + 7 + 8 + 10 + 12}{5} = rac{40}{5} = 8\n$$\n\n### Example 2: Real-World Application\