d 3%. By comparing the sample proportion of defective products found (21 out of 500) to the claimed proportion, you can assess whether there is enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the 5% significance level.',0.5127207040786743,'The Mean (Average), The Mean','ai',NULL,459,'Topic: Inferential Statistics\nQuestion hint: For hypothesis testing of proportions, use the test statistic:\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $p$ is the claimed population proport\nQuestion part ((a)): A manufacturing company claims that **3%** of their products are defective.\n\nA quality inspector suspects this rate has increased and examines a random sample of **500 products**. They find **21 defective products**.\n\nCarry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of significance** to determine if th',627),(27,'2026-01-05 21:46:51.201469','inferential-statistics','For a one-tailed test (right tail) at   = 0.05 =0.05: - Critical z-value:  z = 1.645 z=1.645 explain','For a one-tailed test at a significance level of $\\alpha = 0.05$, the critical z-value of $z = 1.645$ corresponds to the point in the standard normal distribution where 5% of the area lies to the right. This means that if your calculated z-value exceeds 1.645, you would reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis.',0.348134845495224,'The Mean, The Mean (Average)','ai',NULL,459,'Topic: Inferential Statistics\nQuestion hint: For hypothesis testing of proportions, use the test statistic:\n\n$$z = \\frac{\\hat{p} - p}{\\sqrt{\\frac{p(1-p)}{n}}}$$\n\nWhere:\n- $\\hat{p}$ is the sample proportion\n- $p$ is the claimed population proport\nQuestion part ((a)): A manufacturing company claims that **3%** of their products are defective.\n\nA quality inspector suspects this rate has increased and examines a random sample of **500 products**. They find **21 defective products**.\n\nCarry out a hypothesis test at the **5% level of signif